# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bible
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The **Book of Enoch** (also **1 Enoch**; Hebrew: סֵפֶר חֲנוֹךְ, romanized: *Sēfer Ḥănōḵ*; Ge'ez: መጽሐፈ ሄኖክ, romanized: *Maṣḥafa Hēnok*) is an ancient Jewish apocalyptic religious text, ascribed by tradition to the patriarch Enoch who was the father of Methuselah and the great-grandfather of Noah.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The Book of Enoch contains unique material on the origins of demons and Nephilim, why some angels fell from heaven, an explanation of why the Genesis flood was morally necessary, and a prophetic exposition of the thousand-year reign of the Messiah.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Three books are traditionally attributed to Enoch, including the distinct works 2 Enoch and 3 Enoch.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] 1 Enoch is not considered to be canonical scripture by most movements of Judaism or branches of Christianity, although it is part of the biblical canon used by the Ethiopian Jewish community Beta Israel, as well as the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church and Eritrean Orthodox Tewahedo Church.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The older sections of 1 Enoch are estimated to date to c.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] 300–200 BC, and the latest part (Book of Parables) is probably from c.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Scholars believe Enoch was originally written in either Aramaic or Hebrew, the languages first used for Jewish texts.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Ephraim Isaac suggests that the Book of Enoch, like the Book of Daniel, was composed partially in Aramaic and partially in Hebrew.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] No Hebrew version is known to have survived.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Copies of the earlier sections of 1 Enoch were preserved in Aramaic among the Dead Sea Scrolls in the Qumran Caves.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Authors of the New Testament were also familiar with some content of the book.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] A short section of 1 Enoch is cited in the Epistle of Jude, being attributed to "Enoch, the Seventh from Adam" (1 Enoch 60:8).
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The full Book of Enoch survives in its entirety only in the Geʽez translation.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The first part of the Book of Enoch describes the fall of the Watchers, the angels who fathered the angel-human hybrids called Nephilim.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The remainder of the book describes Enoch's revelations and his visits to heaven in the form of travels, visions, and dreams.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Most scholars believe that these five sections were originally independent works (with different dates of composition), themselves a product of much editorial arrangement, and were only later redacted into what is now called 1 Enoch.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Because the Book of Parables is unattested in all except the Ethiopic manuscripts, and because a copy of The Book of Giants appears to be written on the same manuscript as a portion of Enoch, it seems likely that the former may have replaced the latter from the original Enochic pentateuch.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] This first section of the Book of Enoch describes the fall of the Watchers, the angels who fathered the Nephilim, the *bene Elohim*, and narrates the travels of Enoch in the heavens.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] This section is said to have been composed in the 4th or 3rd century BCE according to Western scholars.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] It discusses God coming to Earth on Mount Sinai with his hosts to pass judgment on humankind.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The book also discusses how all things are ordained by God and take place in his time.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The sinners shall perish and the great and the good shall live on in light, joy and peace.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Michael, Uriel, Raphael, and Gabriel appeal to God to judge the inhabitants of the world and the fallen angels.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Uriel is then sent by God to tell Noah of the coming cataclysm and what he needs to do.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The Lord commands Michael to bind the fallen angels.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Chapters 37–71 of the Book of Enoch are referred to as the Book of Parables.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The scholarly debate centers on these chapters.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The Book of Parables appears to be based on the Book of the Watchers, but presents a later development of the idea of final judgment and of eschatology, concerned not only with the destiny of the fallen angels but also that of the evil kings of the earth.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The Book of Parables uses the expression "son of man" for the eschatological protagonist, who is also called "Righteous One", "Chosen One", and "Messiah", and sits on the throne of glory in the final judgment.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The first known use of "Son of Man" as a definite title in Jewish writings is in 1 Enoch, and its use may have played a role in the early Christian understanding and use of the title.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] It has been suggested that the Book of Parables, in its entirety, is a later addition.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Pointing to similarities with the Sibylline Oracles and other earlier works, in 1976, Józef Milik dated the Book of Parables to the third century.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] He believed that the events in the parables were linked to historic events dating from c.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] According to this theory, these chapters were written in later Christian times by a Jewish Christian to enhance Christian beliefs with Enoch's authoritative name.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Knibb followed Milik's reasoning, and suggested that because no fragments of chapter 37–71 were found at Qumran, a later date was likely.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Knibb would continue this line of reasoning in later works.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] In addition to being missing from Qumran, chapters 37–71 are also missing from the Greek translation.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Currently no firm consensus has been reached among scholars as to the date of the writing of the Book of Parables.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Milik's date of as late as AD 270, however, has been rejected by most scholars.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Suter suggests that there is a tendency to date the Book of Parables to between 50 BC – 117 AD.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] In 1893, Robert Charles judged chapter 71 to be a later addition.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] He later changed his opinion and gave an early date for the work between 94 and 64 BC.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Hirsch in *The Jewish Encyclopedia* states that *Son of Man* is found in the Book of Enoch, but never in the original material.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] It occurs in the "Noachian interpolations" (lx.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] 14), wherein it has clearly no other meaning than "man".
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The author of the work misuses or corrupts the titles of the angels.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Charles views the title *Son of Man*, as found in the Book of Parables, as referring to a supernatural person: a messiah who is not of human descent.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] In that part of the Book of Enoch, known as the Similitudes, it has the technical sense of a supernatural Messiah and judge of the world (xlvi.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] 27); universal dominion and preexistence are predicated of him (xlviii.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Though Charles does not admit it, according to Emil G.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Hirsch these passages betray Christian redaction and emendation.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] A number of scholars have suggested that passages in the Book of Parables are Noachian interpolations.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] These passages seem to interrupt the flow of the narrative.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Hannah suggests that these passages are not, in total, novel interpolations, but rather derived from an earlier Noah apocryphon.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] He believes that some interpolations refer to Herod the Great and should be dated to around 4 BC.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] In addition to the theory of Noachian interpolations, which perhaps a majority of scholars support, most scholars currently believe that chapters 70–71 are a later addition in part or in whole.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Chapter 69 ends with, "This is the third parable of Enoch." Like Elijah, Enoch is generally thought to have been brought up to Heaven by God while still alive, but some have suggested that the text refers to Enoch as having died a natural death and ascending to Heaven.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The "Son of Man" is identified with Enoch.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The text implies that Enoch had previously been enthroned in Heaven.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Chapters 70–71 seem to contradict passages earlier in the parable where the Son of Man is a separate entity.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The parable also switches from third person singular to first person singular.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Charlesworth rejects the theory that chapters 70–71 are later additions.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] He believes that no additions were made to the Book of Parables.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] In his earlier work, the implication is that a majority of scholars agreed with him.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Milik first proposed the late date of the Book of Parables, he proposed that the section had replaced an earlier work, the Book of Giants.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The Book of Giants follows the giants, the children of the Watchers, who dream of the coming devastation and ask Enoch to interpret the dreams and to intercede for them.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] One of the recovered fragments of the Book of the Giants from Qumran was written by the same scribe who transcribed a portion of the Book of Enoch, and it is thought that they could belong to the same manuscript (4QEnGiantsaar and 4QEncar).
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Although it is not certain, this would make the Book of Giants the missing piece of Qumran's Enochic pentateuch, later replaced by the Book of Parables in the version of 1 Enoch that was translated into Ge’ez.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Four fragmentary editions of the Astronomical Book were found at Qumran, 4Q208-211.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] 4Q208 and 4Q209 have been dated to the beginning of the 2nd century BC, providing a *terminus ante quem* for the Astronomical Book of the 3rd century BC.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The fragments found in Qumran also include material not contained in the later versions of the Book of Enoch.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] This book contains descriptions of the movement of heavenly bodies and of the firmament, as a knowledge revealed to Enoch in his trips to Heaven guided by Uriel, and it describes a Solar calendar that was later described also in the Book of Jubilees which was used by the Dead Sea sect.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The use of this calendar made it impossible to celebrate the festivals simultaneously with the Temple of Jerusalem.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The year was composed of 364 days, divided into four equal seasons of 91 days each.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Each season was composed of three equal months of thirty days, plus an extra day at the end of the third month.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The whole year was thus composed of exactly 52 weeks, and every calendar day occurred always on the same day of the week.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Each year and each season started always on Wednesday, which was the fourth day of the creation narrated in Genesis, the day when the lights in the sky, the seasons, the days and the years were created.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] It is not known how they used to reconcile this calendar with the tropical year of 365.24 days (at least seven suggestions have been made), and it is not even certain that they felt the need to adjust it.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Some interpret the words sun and stars in the text as referring to sunlight and starlight, allowing them to interpret the passage in a way that does not conflict greatly with the modern cosmological view.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] This interpretation is linguistically possible, since the Akkadian cognate of the Hebrew word for sun, šamšum, can mean sunlight or a day; thus, the term could be used to mean sunlight.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Likewise, the Akkadian cognate of the Hebrew word for star, kakkabum, can refer to an object resembling a star or even a meteor—hence, the term could be used to mean starlight.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The Book of Dream Visions, containing a vision of a history of Israel all the way down to what the majority have interpreted as the Maccabean Revolt, is dated by most to Maccabean times (about 163–142 BC).
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The second dream vision in this section of the Book of Enoch is an allegorical account of the history of Israel, that uses animals to represent human beings and human beings to represent angels.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] One of several hypothetical reconstructions of the meanings in the dream is as follows based on the works of R.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] There are multiple links between the first book and this one, including the outline of the story and the imprisonment of the leaders and destruction of the Nephilim.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] 86:4, 87:3, 88:2, and 89:6 all describe the types of Nephilim that are created during the times described in The Book of the Watchers, though this does not mean that the authors of both books are the same.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Similar references exist in Jubilees 7:21–22.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The book describes their release from the Ark along with three bulls – white, red, and black, which are Shem, Ham, and Japheth – in 89:9.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] It then describes the story of Moses and Aaron (89:13–15), including the miracle of the river splitting in two for them to pass, and the creation of the stone commandments.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Eventually they arrived at a "pleasant and glorious land" (89:40) where they were attacked by dogs (Philistines), foxes (Ammonites, Moabites), and wild boars (Esau).
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] This interpretation is accepted by Dillmann (p.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] It also describes the escape of Elijah the prophet; in 1 Kings 17:2–24, he is fed by "ravens", so if Kings uses a similar analogy, he may have been fed by the Seleucids.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] This part of the book can be taken to be the kingdom splitting into the northern and southern tribes, that is, Israel and Judah, eventually leading to Israel falling to the Assyrians in 721 BC and Judah falling to the Babylonians a little over a century later 587 BC.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] "And He gave them over into the hands of the lions and tigers, and wolves and hyenas, and into the hand of the foxes, and to all the wild beasts, and those wild beasts began to tear in pieces those sheep"; God abandons Israel for they have forsaken him.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] There is also mention of 59 of 70 shepherds with their own seasons; there seems to be some debate on the meaning of this section, some suggesting that it is a reference to the 70 appointed times in 25:11, 9:2, and 1:12.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Another interpretation is the 70 weeks in Daniel 9:24.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] However, the general interpretation is that these are simply angels.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] This section of the book and another section near the end describe the appointment by God of the 70 angels to protect the Israelites from enduring too much harm from the "beasts and birds".
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] "And forthwith I saw how the shepherds pastured for twelve hours, and behold three of those sheep turned back and came and entered and began to build up all that had fallen down of that house".
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] "Cyrus allowed Sheshbazzar, a prince from the tribe of Judah, to bring the Jews from Babylon back to Jerusalem.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Jews were allowed to return with the Temple vessels that the Babylonians had taken.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Construction of the Second Temple began"; this represents the history of ancient Israel and Judah; the temple was completed in 515 BC.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The first part of the next section of the book seems, according to Western scholars, to clearly describe the Maccabean revolt of 167 BCE against the Seleucids.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The following two quotes have been altered from their original form to make the hypothetical meanings of the animal names clear.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] According to this theory, the first sentence most likely refers to the death of High Priest Onias III, whose murder is described in 1 Maccabees 3:33–35 (died c.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The "great horn" clearly is not Mattathias, the initiator of the rebellion, as he dies a natural death, described in 1 Maccabees 2:49.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] It is also not Alexander the Great, as the great horn is interpreted as a warrior who has fought the Macedonians, Seleucids, and Ptolemies.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Judas Maccabeus (167–160 BC) fought all three of these, with a large number of victories against the Seleucids over a great period of time; "they had no power over it".
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] He is also described as "one great horn among six others on the head of a lamb", possibly referring to Maccabeus's five brothers and Mattathias.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] If taken in context of the history from Maccabeus's time, Dillman Chrest Aethiop says the explanation of Verse 13 can be found in 1 Maccabees iii 7; vi.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Maccabeus was eventually killed by the Seleucids at the Battle of Elasa, where he faced "twenty thousand foot soldiers and two thousand cavalry".
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] At one time, it was believed this passage might refer to John Hyrcanus; the only reason for this was that the time between Alexander the Great and John Maccabeus was too short.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] However, it has been asserted that evidence shows that this section does indeed discuss Maccabeus.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] It then describes: "And I saw till a great sword was given to the sheep, and the sheep proceeded against all the beasts of the field to slay them, and all the beasts and the birds of the heaven fled before their face." This might be simply the "power of God": God was with them to avenge the death.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] It may also be Jonathan Apphus taking over command of the rebels to battle on after the death of Judas.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Certain scholars also claim Alexander Jannaeus of Judaea is alluded to in this book.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The most extensive surviving early manuscripts of the Book of Enoch exist in the Geʽez language.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Additionally, there are the manuscripts used by the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church for preparation of the deuterocanonicals from Geʽez into the targumic Amharic in the bilingual Haile Selassie Amharic Bible (*Mashaf qeddus bage'ezenna ba'amaregna yatasafe* 4 vols. c.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Eleven Aramaic-language fragments of the Book of Enoch were found in cave 4 of Qumran in 1948 and are in the care of the Israel Antiquities Authority.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] They were translated for and discussed by Józef Milik and Matthew Black in *The Books of Enoch*.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Other translations were released by Geza Vermes and by Garcia-Martinez.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Milik described the documents as being white or cream in color, blackened in areas, and made of leather that was smooth, thick and stiff.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] They were also partly damaged, with the ink blurred and faint.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The 8th-century work *Chronographia Universalis* by the Byzantine historian George Syncellus preserved some passages of the Book of Enoch in Greek (6:1–9:4, 15:8–16:1).
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] According to Elena Dugan, this Codex was written by two separate scribes and was previously misunderstood as containing errors.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] She suggests that the first scribe actually preserves a valuable text that is not erroneous.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] In fact the text preserves "a thoughtful composition, corresponding to the progression of Enoch's life and culminating in an ascent to heaven".
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The first scribe may have been working earlier, and was possibly unconnected to the second.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] It has been claimed that several small additional fragments in Greek have been found at Qumran (7QEnoch: 7Q4, 7Q8, 7Q10-13), dating about 100 BCE, ranging from 98:11? to 103:15 and written on papyrus with grid lines, but this identification is highly contested.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Portions of 1 Enoch were incorporated into the chronicle of Panodoros (c.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] 400) and thence borrowed by his contemporary Annianos.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] A sixth- or seventh-century fragmentary manuscript contains a Coptic version of the Apocalypse of Weeks.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] How extensive the Coptic text originally was cannot be known.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] It agrees with the Aramaic text against the Ethiopic, but was probably derived from Greek.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Of the Latin translation, only 1:9 and 106:1–18 are known.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The first passage occurs in the Pseudo-Cyprianic *Ad Novatianum* and the Pseudo-Vigilian *Contra Varimadum*; the second was discovered in 1893 by M.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] James in an 8th-century manuscript in the British Museum and published in the same year.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] The only surviving example of *1 Enoch* in Syriac is found in the 12th century *Chronicle* of Michael the Great.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] It is a passage from Book VI and is also known from Syncellus and papyrus.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p01] Michael's source appears to have been a Syriac translation of (part of) the chronicle of Annianos.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Ephraim Isaac, the editor and translator of 1 Enoch in *The Old Testament Pseudepigrapha*, writes that "1 Enoch is clearly composite representing numerous periods and writers", with the various sections spanning from the early pre-Maccabean era (i.e. c.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Nickelsburg writes that "1 Enoch is a collection of Jewish apocalyptic traditions that date from the last three centuries before the common era".
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Paleographic analysis of the Enochic fragments found in the Qumran caves dates the oldest fragments of the Book of the Watchers to 200–150 BC.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Since this work shows evidence of multiple stages of composition, it is probable that this work was already extant in the 3rd century BC.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The same can be said about the Astronomical Book.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Because of these findings, it was no longer possible to claim that the core of the Book of Enoch was composed in the wake of the Maccabean Revolt as a reaction to Hellenization.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Scholars thus had to look for the origins of the Qumranic sections of 1 Enoch in the previous historical period, and the comparison with traditional material of such a time showed that these sections do not draw exclusively on categories and ideas prominent in the Hebrew Bible.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] David Jackson speaks even of an "Enochic Judaism" from which the writers of Qumran scrolls were descended.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Margaret Barker argues, "Enoch is the writing of a very conservative group whose roots go right back to the time of the First Temple".
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Most Qumran fragments are relatively early, with none written from the last period of the Qumranic experience.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The relation between 1 Enoch and the Essenes was noted even before the discovery of the Dead Sea Scrolls.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Classical rabbinic literature is characterized by near silence concerning Enoch.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] It is possible that rabbinic polemics against Enochic texts and traditions might have led to the fall from use of these books in Rabbinic Judaism.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] There is little doubt that 1 Enoch was influential in molding New Testament doctrines about the Messiah, the Son of Man, the messianic kingdom, demonology, the resurrection, and eschatology.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The limits of the influence of 1 Enoch are discussed at length by R.H.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Nickelsburg in their respective translations and commentaries.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The Greek text was known to, and quoted, both positively and negatively, by a number of Church Fathers: references can be found in Justin Martyr, Minucius Felix, Irenaeus, Origen, Cyprian, Hippolytus, Commodianus, Lactantius and Cassian.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] After Cassian and before the modern "rediscovery", some excerpts are given in the Byzantine Empire by the 8th-century monk George Syncellus in his chronography, and in the 9th century, it is listed as an apocryphon of the New Testament by Patriarch Nicephorus.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] He attributes this information to Origen, although no such statement is found anywhere in extant versions of Origen.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Hiob Ludolf, the great Ethiopic scholar of the 17th and 18th centuries, soon claimed it to be a forgery produced by Abba Bahaila Michael.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Better success was achieved by the famous Scottish traveller James Bruce, who, in 1773, returned to Europe from six years in Abyssinia with three copies of a Geʽez version.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] One is preserved in the Bodleian Library, another was presented to the royal library of France, while the third was kept by Bruce.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The copies remained unused until the 19th century; Silvestre de Sacy, in "Notices sur le livre d'Enoch", included extracts of the books with Latin translations (Enoch chapters 1, 2, 5–16, 22, and 32).
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] From this a German translation was made by Rink in 1801.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The first English translation of the Bodleian / Ethiopic manuscript was published in 1821 by Richard Laurence.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] In 1838, Laurence also released the first Geʽez text of 1 Enoch published in the West, under the title: *Libri Enoch Prophetae Versio Aethiopica*.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The text, divided into 105 chapters, was soon considered unreliable as it was the transcription of a single Geʽez manuscript.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] In 1833, Professor Andreas Gottlieb Hoffmann of the University of Jena released a German translation, based on Laurence's work, called *Das Buch Henoch in vollständiger Uebersetzung, mit fortlaufendem Kommentar, ausführlicher Einleitung und erläuternden Excursen*.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Two other translations came out around the same time: one in 1836 called *Enoch Restitutus, or an Attempt* (Rev.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Edward Murray) and one in 1840 called *Prophetae veteres Pseudepigraphi, partim ex Abyssinico vel Hebraico sermonibus Latine bersi* (A.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] However, both are considered to be poor—the 1836 translation most of all—and is discussed in Hoffmann.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The first critical edition, based on five manuscripts, appeared in 1851 as *Liber Henoch, Aethiopice, ad quinque codicum fidem editus, cum variis lectionibus*, by August Dillmann.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] It was followed in 1853 by a German translation of the book by the same author with commentary titled *Das Buch Henoch, übersetzt und erklärt*.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] It was considered the standard edition of 1 Enoch until the work of Charles.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The generation of Enoch scholarship from 1890 to World War I was dominated by Robert Henry Charles.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] His 1893 translation and commentary of the Geʽez text already represented an important advancement, as it was based on ten additional manuscripts.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Charles published a new critical edition of the Geʽez text, using 23 Geʽez manuscripts and all available sources at his time.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The English translation of the reconstructed text appeared in 1912, and the same year in his collection of *The Apocrypha and Pseudepigrapha of the Old Testament*.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The publication, in the early 1950s, of the first Aramaic fragments of 1 Enoch among the Dead Sea Scrolls profoundly changed the study of the document, as it provided evidence of its antiquity and original text.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The official edition of these Aramaic Enoch fragments appeared in 1976, by Jozef Milik.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The renewed interest in 1 Enoch spawned a number of other translations: in Hebrew (A.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] In 1978, a new edition of the Geʽez text was edited by Michael Knibb, with an English translation, while a new commentary appeared in 1985 by Matthew Black.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Nickelsburg published the first volume of a comprehensive commentary on 1 Enoch in the Hermeneia series.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Since the year 2000, the Enoch seminar has devoted several meetings to the Enoch literature and has become the center of a lively debate concerning the hypothesis that the Enoch literature attests the presence of an autonomous non-Mosaic tradition of dissent in Second Temple Judaism.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Jay Winter published his translation of the Ethiopian texts in his *Complete Book of Enoch, Standard English Version* in 2015.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Judging by the number of copies found in the Dead Sea Scrolls, the Book of Enoch was widely read during the Second Temple period.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Today, the Ethiopian Beta Israel community of Haymanot Jews is the only Jewish group that accepts the Book of Enoch as canonical and still preserves it in its liturgical language of Geʽez, where it plays a central role in worship.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] However, the Book of Enoch was excluded from both the formal canon of the Tanakh and the Septuagint and therefore, also from the writings known today as the Deuterocanon.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Possible reasons for Enoch's exclusion from the canon of Rabbinic Judaism include that its teachings on fallen angels and the corruptibility of man did not accord with orthodox Jewish teaching.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Its focus on mystical and apocalyptic themes rather than legal and ethical concerns also differs from Rabbinic Judaism.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] "The term Pseudepigrapha means false writings, i.e., writings whose authors used false names such as biblical heroes like Ezra and Enoch.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] By the fifth century, the Book of Enoch was mostly excluded from Christian biblical canons, and it is now regarded as scripture only by the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church and the Eritrean Orthodox Tewahedo Church.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] He cometh with ten thousands of His Saints to execute judgment upon all, and to destroy all the ungodly: And to convict all flesh of all the works of their ungodliness which they have ungodly committed, and of all the hard things which ungodly sinners have spoken against Him.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Compare this also with what may be the original source of 1 Enoch 1:9 in Deuteronomy 33:2: In "He cometh with ten thousands of His holy ones".
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] According to Charles (1912), this "... text reproduces the Masoretic of Deuteronomy 33 in reading אָתָא‎ = ἔρχεται, whereas the three Targums, the Syriac and Vulgate read אִתֹּה‎, = μετ' αὐτοῦ.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The reading אתא‎ is recognized as original.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Other English translations of this passage vary widely.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] According to John Barton, under the heading of canonicity, it is not enough to merely demonstrate that something is quoted.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Instead, it is necessary to demonstrate the nature of the quotation.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] In the case of the Jude 1:14 quotation of 1 Enoch 1:9, it would be difficult to argue that Jude does not quote Enoch as a historical prophet since he cites Enoch by name.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] However, there remains a question as to whether the author of Jude attributed the quotation to the historical Enoch before the flood or to a midrash on Deuteronomy 33:2–3.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The Greek text might seem unusual in stating that "Enoch the Seventh from Adam" prophesied "to" (dative case) not "of" (genitive case) the men.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] However, this Greek grammar might indicate the meaning "against them" – the dative τούτοις as a dative of disadvantage (*dativus incommodi*).
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Davids (2006) points to the Dead Sea Scrolls evidence but leaves it open as to whether Jude viewed 1 Enoch as canon, deuterocanon, or otherwise: "Did Jude, then, consider this scripture to be like Genesis or Isaiah?
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Certainly he did consider it authoritative, a true word from God.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] We cannot tell whether he ranked it alongside other prophetic books such as Isaiah and Jeremiah.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The attribution "Enoch the Seventh from Adam" is apparently itself a section heading taken from 1 Enoch (1 Enoch 60:8 and Jude 1:14a) and not from Genesis.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Enoch's name appears in Luke 3:37 as being the father of Methuselah, in the patrilineage of Jesus that is traced back to Adam.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Enoch is referred to directly in the Epistle to the Hebrews.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The epistle mentions that Enoch received testimony from God before his translation, which may be a reference to 1 Enoch.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] It has also been suggested that the First Epistle of Peter (1 Peter 3:19–20) and the Second Epistle of Peter (2 Peter 2:4–5) make reference to some Enochian material.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Other references also include Jude 1:6, and First Corinthians (1 Corinthians 11:10), according to Heinrich August Wilhelm Meyer.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] According to the Pulpit Commentary, Luke 1:19 may mirror Enoch, where archangels, including Gabriel, stand before the presence of the Lord.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Bible scholar Simon Gathercole has indicated that Luke 10:18 may be drawing on eschatological passages and the cosmology of Enoch, with the primeval descent of Satan being related to the downfall of the Watchers.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] However, Gathercole critiques this view on the enigmatic verse, positing that the reference is instead a vision about a future event in the last days.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The Book of Enoch was considered as scripture in the Epistle of Barnabas (4:3) and by some of the early Church Fathers, such as Athenagoras, Clement of Alexandria, and Tertullian, who wrote c.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] 200 that the Jews had rejected the Book of Enoch because it purportedly contained prophecies about Jesus.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints does not consider 1 Enoch to be part of its standard canon, although it believes that a purported "original" Book of Enoch was an inspired book.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The Book of Moses, first published in the 1830s by this church, is part of its standard works and has a section that claims to contain extracts from the "original" Book of Enoch.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] This section has a number of similarities to 1 Enoch and other Enoch texts, including 2 Enoch, 3 Enoch, and *The Book of Giants*.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The Enoch section of the Book of Moses is believed by the Church to contain extracts from "the ministry, teachings, and visions of Enoch", though it does not contain the entire Book of Enoch itself.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The Church considers the portions of the other texts that match its Enoch excerpts to be inspired, while not rejecting but withholding judgment on the remainder.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Some of the fallen angels that are given in 1 Enoch have other names, such as *Ramel* ('morning of God'), who becomes Azazel, and is also called *Gadriel* ('wall of God') in Chapter 68.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Another example is that *Araqiel* ('Earth of God') becomes *Aretstikapha* ('world of distortion') in Chapter 68.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The name suffix *-el* comes from the Hebrew text and the Lord’s name Emmanuel, (see list of names referring to El), and is used in the names of high-ranking angels.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The archangels' names all include *-el*, such as *Uriel* ('flame of God') and *Michael* ('who is like God').
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] Enochic studies have traditionally been historical, focusing on the meanings of the text for its ancient audiences.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] 1 Enoch counts as Old Testament scripture in the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church and has played a significant role in its theology, especially via the *andemta* tradition of interpretation.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] In 2015 a group of scholars from Ethiopia and other countries held meetings in Ethiopia and the UK to explore the significance of Enoch for contemporary theology.
[src:bible/1-enoch-p02] The initial outcome was a collection of essays published in 2017 on various theological topics, including justice, political theology, the environment, the identity of the Son of Man, suffering and evil.
[src:bible/1-esdras] As part of the Septuagint translation, it is now regarded as canonical in the churches of the East, but apocryphal in the West; either presented in a separate section or excluded altogether.
[src:bible/1-esdras] For example, it is listed among the Apocrypha in Article VI of the Thirty-Nine Articles of the Church of England.
[src:bible/1-esdras] 1 Esdras is found in Origen's *Hexapla*.
[src:bible/1-esdras] The Greek Septuagint, the Old Latin bible and related bible versions include both Esdras Αʹ (English title: 1 Esdras) and Esdras Βʹ (Ezra–Nehemiah) as separate books.
[src:bible/1-esdras] There is scope for considerable confusion with references to 1 Esdras.
[src:bible/1-esdras] The name refers primarily to translations of the original Greek 'Esdras A'.
[src:bible/1-esdras] The Septuagint calls it Esdras A, and the Vetus Latina calls it 1 Esdras, while the Vulgate calls it 3 Esdras.
[src:bible/1-esdras] 1 Esdras contains the whole of Ezra with the addition of one section; its verses are numbered differently.
[src:bible/1-esdras] Just as Ezra begins with the last two verses of 2 Chronicles, 1 Esdras begins with the last two chapters, beginning with Josiah's celebration of the Passover; this suggests that Chronicles and Esdras may have been read as one book at some time in the past.
[src:bible/1-esdras] Ezra 4:6 includes a reference to a King Ahasuerus.
[src:bible/1-esdras] Etymologically, Ahasuerus is the same as Xerxes, who reigned between Darius I and Artaxerxes I.
[src:bible/1-esdras] In 1 Esdras, the section is reorganized, leading up to the additional section, and the reference to Ahasuerus is removed.
[src:bible/1-esdras] The additional section begins with a story known variously as the "Darius contest", the "Tale of the Three Guardsmen", or the "Story of the Three Youths", which was interpolated into 1 Esdras at 3:1 to 4:42.
[src:bible/1-esdras] This section forms the core of 1 Esdras with Ezra 5, which together are arranged in a literary chiasm around the celebration in Jerusalem at the exiles' return.
[src:bible/1-esdras] This chiastic core forms 1 Esdras into a complete literary unit, allowing it to stand independently from the Book of Nehemiah.
[src:bible/1-esdras] Yamauchi, believe that Nehemiah came back to Jerusalem *before* Ezra.
[src:bible/1-esdras] The purpose of the book seems to be retelling the Return to Zion in a way that it revolved around the story of the dispute among the courtiers, the 'Tale of the Three Guardsmen'.
[src:bible/1-esdras] Since there are various discrepancies in the account, most scholars hold that the work was written by more than one author.
[src:bible/1-esdras] However, some scholars believe that this work may have been the original, or at least the more authoritative.
[src:bible/1-esdras] Most scholars agree that the original language of the work was Aramaic and Hebrew, with a few arguing for the originality of the Greek.
[src:bible/1-esdras] The text contains similarities to the vocabulary in the Book of Daniel and II Maccabees, and it is presumed that the authors came either from Lower Egypt or Palestine and wrote during the Seleucid period.
[src:bible/1-esdras] Assuming this theory is correct, many scholars consider the possibility that the book made use of an Aramaic chronicle.
[src:bible/1-esdras] Josephus makes use of 1 Esdras, which he treats as Scripture, while generally disregarding the canonical text of Ezra–Nehemiah.
[src:bible/1-esdras] Some scholars believe that the composition is likely to have taken place in the second century BC.
[src:bible/1-esdras] Many Protestant and Catholic scholars assign no historical value to the sections of the book not duplicated in Ezra–Nehemiah.
[src:bible/1-esdras] The citations of the other books of the Bible, however, provide an early alternative to the Septuagint for those texts, which increases its value to scholars.
[src:bible/1-esdras] In the current Greek texts, the book breaks off in the middle of a sentence; that particular verse thus had to be reconstructed from an early Latin translation.
[src:bible/1-esdras] However, it is generally presumed that the original work extended to the Feast of Tabernacles, as described in Nehemiah 8:13–18.
[src:bible/1-esdras] An additional difficulty with the text appears to readers who are unfamiliar with chiastic structures common in Semitic literature.
[src:bible/1-esdras] If the text is assumed to be a Western-style, purely linear narrative, then Artaxerxes seems to be mentioned before Darius, who is mentioned before Cyrus.
[src:bible/1-esdras] Some scholars, including Joseph Blenkinsopp in his 1988 commentary on Ezra–Nehemiah, hold that the book is a late 2nd/early 1st century BC revision of Esdras and Esdras β, while others such as L.
[src:bible/1-esdras] Grabbe believe it to be independent of the Hebrew-language Ezra–Nehemiah.
[src:bible/1-esdras] The book was widely quoted by early Christian authors and it found a place in Origen's *Hexapla*.
[src:bible/1-esdras] In early Latin traditions, Ezra, Nehemiah, 1 Esdras and 2 Esdras were known, respectively, as 1 Esdras, 2 Esdras, 3 Esdras (‘the Greek Esdras’) and 4 Esdras.
[src:bible/1-esdras] In the Vulgate, I Esdras is considered to be Ezra, II Esdras to be Nehemiah, III Esdras to be 1 Esdras, and IV Esdras to be 2 Esdras.
[src:bible/1-esdras] For Jerome, III Esdras and IV Esdras were apocryphal.
[src:bible/1-esdras] As Jerome's Vulgate version of the Bible gradually achieved dominance in Western Christianity, III Esdras no longer circulated.
[src:bible/1-esdras] From the 13th century onwards, Vulgate Bibles produced in Paris reintroduced a Latin text of 1 Esdras, in response to commercial demand.
[src:bible/1-esdras] However, the use of the book continued in the Eastern Church, and it remains a part of the Eastern Orthodox canon.
[src:bible/1-esdras] At the Council of Trent, only 3 bishops voted for an explicit rejection of the books of Esdras; the overwhelming majority "withheld any explicit decision on these books": thus "the question of Esdras' canonical status was left theoretically open".
[src:bible/1-esdras] In the Roman rite liturgy, 1 Esdras is used in the Missal of 1962 in the offertory prayer of a Votive Mass for the election of a Pope.
[src:bible/1-esdras] The book normally called 1 Esdras is numbered differently among various versions of the Bible.
[src:bible/1-esdras] In most editions of the Septuagint, the book is titled in Greek: Ἔσδρας Αʹ and is placed before the single book of Ezra–Nehemiah, which is titled in Greek: Ἔσδρας Βʹ.
[src:bible/1-esdras] 1 Esdras is called 3 Esdras in the Latin Vulgate, which was translation from the Greek version of the Septuagint called Esdras A.
[src:bible/1-esdras] The Vulgate denoted 1 Esdras (Ezra) and 2 Esdras (Nehemiah) respectively.
[src:bible/1-esdras] 3 Esdras continues to be accepted as canonical by Eastern Orthodoxy and the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church, with 4 Esdras varying in canonicity between particular denominations within the Eastern churches.
[src:bible/1-esdras] The Slavonic Bible refers to this book as 2 Esdras, the Romanian Synodal Version refers to it as III Ezdra, and the Ethiopic Bible calls it "Ezra Kali", i.e.
[src:bible/1-esdras] The King James Version and many successive English translations, including the RSV, NRSV, NEB, REB, and GNB, refer to "1 Esdras".
[src:bible/1-esdras] The Clementine Vulgate and its derivative translations refer to 3 Esdras.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The author is anonymous, but he probably wrote in the newly independent Hasmonean kingdom after the success of the Maccabean Revolt in the late 2nd century BC.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] 1 Maccabees was probably written in Hebrew originally.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] However, this original Hebrew has been lost, and the work survives only in translation in Koine Greek in the Septuagint, the Greek version of the Jewish scriptures.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The Septuagint was preserved by Christians as the basis for the Christian Old Testament.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] It became part of the deuterocanon in early Christianity.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The book is held as canonical scripture today in the Catholic, Eastern Orthodox, and Oriental Orthodox churches (except for the Orthodox Tewahedo).
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The book is not included in the Hebrew Bible (Tanakh) and is not recognized as canonical by Protestant denominations or any of the major branches of Judaism.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Some Protestants include the book in the biblical apocrypha, as material useful for background and edification but not canonical.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Rabbinic Judaism generally disapproved of the rule of the Hasmonean dynasty, but the book is openly pro-Hasmonean, one of several factors contributing to its lack of enthusiasm within later Judaism.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] 1 Maccabees is best known for its account of the recapture of Jerusalem in the year 164 BC and rededication of the Second Temple: the origin behind the Jewish holiday of Hanukkah.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The author of 1 Maccabees is anonymous and unknown.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] He wrote in the post-independence Hasmonean kingdom, probably during the reign of High Priest John Hyrcanus (r.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] 134–104 BC), with a few scholars suggesting that early in the reign of Alexander Jannaeus (r.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] All agree that the book was written before 63 BC, as the author shows great admiration toward Rome and does not know of the Roman general Pompey conquering Jerusalem and reducing the Hasmonean kingdom to a client state of the Roman Republic in that year.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] He was likely a court historian or equivalent.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The author appears to be very familiar with Judea and its geography, but appears less well-informed about the wider Hellenistic world.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The entire work is generally considered to be a unity composed by a single author on both philological and thematic grounds, although there are occasional short passages sometimes contested as potentially being added at a later date.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The title "1 Maccabees" is not the original title of the work.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Rather, it comes from the Septuagint, which gave it that title to distinguish it from the other books of the Maccabees.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] In the book itself, "Maccabee" is used solely as a personal title for Judah Maccabee (Latinized as Judas Maccabeus).
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Judas's *Maccabee* title is generally tied to the Aramaic word *maqqaba* ("makebet" in modern Hebrew), "hammer" or "sledgehammer".
[src:bible/1-maccabees] It is unknown how he got this epithet; most presume it was in recognition of his prowess in battle.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The word "Maccabees" in plural, however, does not appear to have been used until centuries after the Maccabean Revolt.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] At first, it was used to describe the martyrs described in 2 Maccabees.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] It later became a title given to the rebels as a whole around the 3rd–5th century AD, hence the Septuagint naming the works as books of the Maccabees.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] This usage of "Maccabees" as a group-term may have originated in Greek, as no usage of it in Hebrew to refer to the rebels survives from any era earlier than the 19th century.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Eusebius, in his book *Church History*, quotes Origen of Alexandria who says the title of the work was *Sarbēth Sabanaiel*, an enigmatic Greek transliteration from a putative Hebrew original title.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] It is thought that the most likely parts are the Aramaic *səpar* ("book"), bêt ("house" or "dynasty"), and 'ēl ("God").
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The book was probably originally written in Hebrew.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Both Origen and Jerome claim to have seen a Hebrew text of 1 Maccabees.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The surviving Greek script has Hebraisms and Hebrew idioms.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] It also seems to have been written in Judea where knowledge of Hebrew was more widespread.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] If it really was originally written in Greek, then the author was intentionally imitating Hebrew style in Greek.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The book is not written in colloquial "common" Koine Greek of the 2nd century BC, but rather a more archaic style of Greek consciously imitative of the style of older scriptures.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] It frequently imitates biblical phraseology and directly cites biblical precedents.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The English equivalent would be writing new books in the style of the King James Version of the Bible.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The book is generally classed as a historical book of the Bible.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] While the main focus is a recounting of history, some consider the book to have merit as literary art as well.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The narrative is primarily prose text, but is interrupted by seven poetic sections, which imitate classical Hebrew poetry.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] These include four laments and three hymns of praise.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Various historical documents are included as well, notably of negotiations and letters with the Roman Republic and Hellenistic Sparta.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The setting of the book is about a century and a half after the conquest of Judea by the Greeks under Alexander the Great, after Alexander's empire had been divided so that Judea had become part of the Greek Seleucid Empire.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] It tells how the Greek ruler Antiochus IV Epiphanes attempted to suppress the practice of basic Jewish law, resulting in the Maccabean Revolt.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The book covers the whole of the revolt, from 175 to 134 BC, highlighting how the salvation of the Jewish people in this crisis came through Mattathias' family, particularly his sons, Judas Maccabeus, Jonathan Apphus, and Simon Thassi, and Simon's son, John Hyrcanus.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The doctrine expressed in the book reflects traditional Jewish teaching, without later doctrines found, for example, in 2 Maccabees.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The First Book of Maccabees also gives a list of Jewish colonies scattered elsewhere through the Mediterranean at the time.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] In the first chapter, Alexander the Great conquers the territory of Judea, and is later succeeded by the Seleucid Antiochus IV Epiphanes.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] After successfully invading the Ptolemaic Kingdom of Egypt, Antiochus IV captures Jerusalem and removes the sacred objects from the Temple in Jerusalem, slaughtering many Jews.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] He then imposes a tax and establishes a fortress in Jerusalem.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Antiochus then tries to suppress public observance of Jewish laws, in an attempt to secure control over the Jews.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] In 168 BC, he desecrates the Temple by setting up an "abomination of desolation" (establishing rites of pagan observance in the Temple, or sacrificing an unclean animal on the altar in the Holy of Holies).
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Antiochus forbids both circumcision and possession of Jewish scriptures on pain of death.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] He forbids observance of the sabbath and the offering of sacrifices at the Temple.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] He also requires Jewish leaders to sacrifice to idols.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] While enforcement may be targeting only Jewish leaders, ordinary Jews were also killed as a warning to others.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Hellenization included the construction of gymnasia in Jerusalem.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Among other effects, this discouraged the Jewish rite of circumcision even further, which had already been officially forbidden; a man's state could not be concealed in the gymnasium, where men trained and socialized in the nude.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] However, 1 Maccabees also insists that there were many Jews who sought out or welcomed the introduction of Greek culture.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] According to the text, some Jewish men even engaged in foreskin restoration in order to pass as fully Greek.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The narrative reports that news of the desolation reaches Mattathias and his five sons, a priestly family who live in Modein.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Mattathias calls upon people loyal to the traditions of Israel to oppose the invaders and the Jewish Hellenizers, and his sons begin a military campaign against them.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] There is one complete loss of a thousand Jews (men, women, and children) to Antiochus when the Jewish defenders refuse to fight on the Sabbath.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The other Jews then reason that, when attacked, they must fight even on the holy day.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] In 165 BC the Temple is freed and reconsecrated, so that ritual sacrifices may begin again.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The festival of Hanukkah is instituted by Judas Maccabeus and his brothers to celebrate this event (1 Maccabees 4:59).
[src:bible/1-maccabees] More wars involving Judas and his brothers Simon and Jonathan are reported in chapters 5, 6 and 7.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Chapter 6 reports the last days of Antiochus Epiphanes and the accession of his young son Antiochus V Eupator to the throne.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] In chapter 8, Judas seeks an alliance with the Roman Republic, aiming to remove the Greeks.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Jewish historian Uriel Rappaport asserts that "the majority of scholars today accept the authenticity of this document".
[src:bible/1-maccabees] After the death of Judas and a period of lawlessness, he is succeeded by his brother Jonathan Apphus, whose battles with the Greek general Bacchides are recounted in chapter 9.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Jonathan becomes high priest (1 Maccabees 10:20).
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Demetrius' death is reported in 1 Maccabees 10:50, and Ptolemy VI Philometor and Alexander Balas, claimant to the Seleucid throne, enter into an agreement under which Alexander marries Cleopatra Thea, Ptolemy's daughter (1 Maccabees 10:58).
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Maccabees does not mention the involvement of the mercenaries who are mentioned in other accounts, whereas other accounts do not mention the Jewish involvement.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Ultimately the relationship between Jonathan and Demetrius breaks down: Maccabees' opinion is that Demetrius "broke his word about all that he had promised; he became estranged from Jonathan and did not repay the favors that Jonathan had done him, but treated him very harshly".
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Proposed alliances with Rome and with Areus of Sparta are covered in 1 Maccabees 12:1–23.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Jonathan's capture in 143 BC, having been double-crossed by Diodotus Tryphon, is recorded in 1 Maccabees 12:48.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Simon follows Jonathan as the next Jewish leader "in place of Judas and your brother Jonathan", taking on civil, military and liturgical roles: "great high priest, governor, and leader of the Jews".
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Simon fortifies Jerusalem (1 Maccabees 13:10) and secures the reoccupation of Joppa (1 Maccabees 13:11), leading the people in peace and prosperity until he is murdered by agents of Ptolemy, son of Abubus, who had been named governor of the region by the Macedonian Greeks.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The period of peace and prosperity is celebrated in a biblical-style poetic passage, the "Eulogy of Simon", which Rappaport considers to be "one of the most important poetic passages in 1 Maccabees".
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Simon is succeeded by his son, John, referred to by Josephus as John Hyrcanus.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The author propagates "Hasmonean propaganda" in the sense of upholding the righteousness of the Hasmoneans and their just claim to rule the Hasmonean kingdom.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The Hasmoneans were not an obvious choice to be rulers; they did not descend from the priestly line of Zadok that had taken the office of High Priest for generations at the point of the Maccabean Revolt.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The author seeks to promote the view that the Hasmoneans were indeed God's new chosen and would-be rulers in line with heroes of the Hebrew Bible.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Various passages call back to Biblical passages such as Joshua's conquests or the battle of David and Goliath and equate the Hasmoneans' deeds with the earlier stories.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Antipathy toward the Seleucid-friendly Hellenizing Jews is unsurprising, as they were enemies in war, but 1 Maccabees extends criticism to internal Jewish opponents of the Hasmoneans as well.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] In 1 Maccabees, those dissatisfied with the Hasmoneans "hated their nation" as a whole; the Hasmoneans were equated with Judea itself.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Jews who complain about Judas's activities "bring to the king an accusation against the people".
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The book dismisses a defeat suffered by other commanders named Joseph and Azariah as because "they did not listen to Judas and his brothers.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] But they did not belong to the family of those men through whom deliverance was given to Israel." All of this makes clear that God has specifically chosen a new dynasty to rule Judea, the Hasmoneans.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] While the book holds all the Hasmoneans in high regard, it praises Simon Thassi in particular, the person who would pass the High Priesthood to his sons and establish the dynasty.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] In Chapter 2, there is a line from a dying Mattathias who tells his sons to always listen to Simon and that "he shall be your father", seemingly praising him even over Judas.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Chapter 14 also features a long panegyric praising Simon as a worthy leader.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The school of philosophy seen in 1 Maccabees is often thought to be a predecessor to the philosophy of the Sadducees in later eras.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Notably, the author makes no reference to the idea of a bodily resurrection, which the Sadducees opposed.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] That said, contemporary textual sources of the Sadducees are scant, so it is difficult to know for sure.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The book also comes across as dismissive of martyrdom and passive approaches to resistance, seeing such gestures as futile and pointless.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Some scholars go even farther than dismissive; Jonathan A.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Goldstein wrote that the author had "considerable contempt for martyrs".
[src:bible/1-maccabees] For the author, bold military action while living is the proper response to oppression.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The author sees the revolt as divinely ordained, but downplays direct divine intervention such as miracles.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Rather, the author interprets events as God using the military genius of Judas Maccabeus and his brothers as the instrument to achieve the liberation of Judea.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] One of the most notable and unusual aspects of the book of 1 Maccabees by absence is the lack of any direct mention of God.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] No angels or miracles come to save the Jews; rather, it is the divinely-approved firm leadership of the Hasmoneans that leads to victory.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The book 2 Maccabees, preserved with 1 Maccabees in the Septuagint, provides a striking contrast in theology, and the works are often compared.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] 2 Maccabees interprets the misfortunes of the Jews as God's punishment for their own sins; the author of 1 Maccabees depicts the problems as due to the external evil of Antiochus IV and his generals, not as a cleansing ordeal that was in some sense divine will.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The book draws a sharp contrast between Jews and Gentiles, similar to the books of Ezra and Nehemiah.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The persecution of Antiochus IV presumably radicalized the Jews.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] That said, the author is still proud of forging alliances with others, citing negotiations with the Roman Republic and Sparta.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Uriel Rappaport called it emblematic of Hasmonean politics, in general: that the Hasmonean state was an explicitly Jewish one that sought to separate itself from polytheism, yet was pragmatic and sought allies where they could be found.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] 1 Maccabees is the most extensive source of information on events in Judea from 175 to 135 BC.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] It has traditionally been considered highly trustworthy, though it is, to some extent, the "official" version of history from the Hasmonean and Maccabean points of view.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Bezalel Bar-Kochva praises it as among the better military historiography of the period.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] He argues that the author was likely an eyewitness to at least some of the battles described, given his great accuracy and plausibility in describing terrain and troop movements, and was able to obtain firsthand accounts from others in interviews.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] He also cites the fact that it makes various "admissions against interest" such as openly describing rebel military defeats, unlike 2 Maccabees, which obscures or omits such matters.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Goldstein argues that the book was imitative of older scriptures not merely in linguistic style, but also in content; that is, the author adjusted or invented events to make them fit biblical parallels better.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Pope Damasus I's Council of Rome in 382, if the Gelasian Decree is correctly associated with it, issued a Christian biblical canon identical to the list given at Trent, including the two books of Maccabees.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Origen of Alexandria (253), Augustine of Hippo (c.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] 397 AD), Pope Innocent I (405), Synod of Hippo (393), the Council of Carthage (397), the Council of Carthage (419), the Apostolic Canons, the Council of Florence (1442), and the Council of Trent (1546) listed the first two books of Maccabees as canonical.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] During the Protestant Reformation, the book—along with other books in the Catholic deuterocanon—was classed as biblical apocrypha in Protestantism: material useful for background but not canonical.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The 1643 Westminster Confession of Faith declared that the books "are of no authority in the Church of God, not to be any otherwise approved", for example.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The book was never included in the Hebrew Bible (Tanakh) and is not canonical by any mainstream movements of Judaism.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Later Jewish leaders viewed the rule of the Hasmonean dynasty poorly for several reasons, and a document so openly celebratory of them was problematic.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Even in stories set during the Maccabean period, references to Judas by name were explicitly removed to avoid hero-worship of the Hasmonean line.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The Jewish historian Josephus of the 1st century AD almost certainly read 1 Maccabees in Greek.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] He extensively uses the first thirteen chapters of it in Books 12 and 13 of his work *Jewish Antiquities*, paraphrasing it directly in parts, although supplementing it with other Greek histories such as Nicolaus of Damascus.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] He may also have consulted it for Book 1 of *The Jewish War*.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] It is not known whether Josephus's copy of 1 Maccabees was missing the final three chapters, or he simply found a better source for that era of history.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] 1 Maccabees is only very rarely quoted or referenced by the Church Fathers in the era of early Christianity.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] When Christians of the Roman Empire discussed the Maccabees, it was usually in reference to the "Maccabean martyrs" described in 2 Maccabees 6 and 2 Maccabees 7, as they were seen as models and precursors to Christian martyrs.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] As 1 Maccabees has very little to say about the martyrs, it correspondingly was not cited or read.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] During the Crusades, Pope Urban II and other church leaders used 1 Maccabees to justify the concept of holy war against the Muslim kingdoms controlling the holy city of Jerusalem.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Admired crusaders such as Baldwin I and Godfrey of Bouillon were explicitly compared to Judas Maccabeus, and material from 1 Maccabees was quoted in regards to their deeds.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] 1 Maccabees was also cited during the 11th–12th century Investiture Controversy concerning whether monarchs had the authority to appoint bishops, or only the Pope.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] 1 Maccabees includes passages describing the appointment of Jonathan and Simon by Seleucid authorities, so it was generally cited by the side of those who favored royal appointment of bishops.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] 1 Maccabees is part of the intertestamental Apocrypha section of the Bible used in the Lutheran Churches and the Anglican Communion.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Scripture readings from the Apocrypha are included in the lectionaries of the Lutheran Churches.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] With regard to Anglicanism, in the Church of England's lectionary of 1922 in the *Book of Common Prayer*, 1st Maccabees is appointed annually to be read in late summer/early autumn.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The texts regarding the martyrdoms under Antiochus IV in 1 Maccabees and 2 Maccabees are read by Anabaptist Christians, who faced persecution in their history.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] As noted above, if ancient manuscripts of the hypothesized original Hebrew version existed, they have been lost.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The Greek text is extant in two of the three oldest codices of the Greek Septuagint: the Codex Sinaiticus and Codex Alexandrinus.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Pre-modern translations of the work were made in Latin, Syriac, and Armenian.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] The Latin translation is sometimes useful to identify certain changes made by Lucian of Antioch to the Greek text.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] With the advent of the printing press that obviated the need for scribes to manually and repeatedly copy such works, 1 Maccabees became more widely available.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] It was included in standard printed Christian Bibles in the deuterocanon section.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] A Greek version of the text was printed for the first time in 1514–1517 in the Complutensian Polyglot Bible.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] Werner Kappler published a critical edition of the Greek text in 1936, an eclectic compilation of the various surviving manuscripts and the best construction of the original text.
[src:bible/1-maccabees] More recent English language versions of the Bible which contain 1 Maccabees include the New Revised Standard Version (NRSV), Good News Translation (GNT), New American Bible, Revised Edition (NABRE), and the Knox Bible.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The **1838 Mormon War**, also known as the **Missouri Mormon War**, was a series of armed conflicts between Mormons (Latter Day Saints) and other settlers in northern Missouri during the summer and fall of 1838.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Initially characterized by mutual vigilante violence, it escalated into direct intervention by the Missouri state militia.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The conflict concluded with the issuance of the Missouri Executive Order 44, which mandated the extermination or the expulsion of the Mormons from the state.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Early Latter Day Saints settled in western Missouri beginning in 1830, driven by revelations instructing them to "gather" in two main centers: Kirtland, Ohio, and Jackson County, Missouri.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Facing increasing hostility from neighboring settlers, an 1833 crisis resulted in their forceful eviction from Jackson County by vigilantes.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The Missouri legislature went on to create Caldwell County in 1836 as a "compromise" for displaced Mormon settlers; however, the relocation of Mormon leaders from Kirtland in early 1838 intensified fears of Mormon consolidation and expansion in Missouri.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Violence reignited on August 6, 1838, after a group attempted to prevent Mormons from voting in Gallatin, Daviess County, Missouri, catalyzing the formation of vigilance committees that sought to expel the Mormons from Missouri.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Local militia largely failed to quell the unrest, which rapidly escalated into a series of raids and counter-raids.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Key engagements included the Battle of Crooked River (October 24), and the Haun's Mill Massacre (October 30) where anti-Mormon vigilantes killed 17 unarmed Latter Day Saints.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The state's response to the conflict provoked widespread controversy and severely damaged Boggs's political standing.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The war resulted in 22 deaths and the displacement of 10,000 Latter Day Saints, most seeking refuge in the state of Illinois.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] In spring of 1830, Joseph Smith published the Book of Mormon and founded the Church of Christ, a restorationist church.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] While Smith settled in Kirtland, Ohio, he sent some of his close associates to western Missouri to proselytize among Native Americans.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] After encountering some moderate success, Mormons began making permanent settlements in Jackson County, Missouri in 1831.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] In August 1831, Smith announced that Independence, Missouri and the surrounding area would become the "centerplace" of his planned "City of Zion"—a gathering place within Mormon millennial theology.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Mormon leadership in Missouri was instructed to make extensive land purchases in the area to be distributed to incoming members.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Under the auspice of Mormon leaders in Kirtland, settlers trickled to the county during the following months.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] By 1833, Mormons numbered over a thousand, representing about a third and as much as half of the county's population.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The Mormon settlers' religious, cultural, and political differences, economic cohesion, their perceived affinity for neighboring Native American tribes, and their divine claims to the land of "Zion" contributed to growing animosity.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Most Latter Day Saint settlers were originally from New England and the Ohio Valley and, unlike their southern neighbors, generally opposed slavery.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] In July 1833, a local meeting was held by non-Mormon residents in Independence after an article titled "Free People of Color" was published in the Mormon newspaper, *The Evening and Morning Star.* The article's mention of the potential arrival of free black converts was particularly controversial.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Attendees contended that the Mormons threatened civil society, and that local laws were insufficient to address the perceived dangers.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] They resolved to remove the Mormons, "peaceably if we can, forcibly if we must." The group then agreed to destroy the newspaper's printing press and demanded that Mormon leaders pledge to halt their activities and leave the county.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] When the Mormons refused, they then targeted and ransacked the Mormon storehouse in Independence.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Mormon settlements in the outskirts of the city were increasingly harassed and raided throughout the summer and fall of 1833.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] By November 1833, vigilantes had forcefully expelled the Mormons from Jackson County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The expulsion from Jackson County informed the patterns of conflict between the Mormons and other Missouri residents over the course of the Mormon war.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The expelled Mormons sought refuge in the neighboring counties, especially in Clay County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Lilburn Boggs, who would later be the Governor of Missouri during the 1838 war, was Lieutenant Governor and a Jackson County resident at the time.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Despite appeals and legal efforts, the non-Mormons in Jackson refused to allow the Mormons to return.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Reimbursement for confiscated and damaged property was denied.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Mormons refused to sell their lands in the county, hoping that the government would eventually help them reclaim them.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] In 1834, Mormons attempted to effect a return to Jackson County with a quasi-military expedition known as Zion's Camp, but this effort also failed when the governor did not provide the expected support.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Recognizing the need for a more permanent solution, Alexander William Doniphan of the Missouri legislature proposed the creation of a new county specifically for Mormon settlement.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] In 1836, the Missouri legislature passed a law establishing Caldwell County, with Far West as its seat.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Mormons had already begun buying land in the proposed county, including areas that were carved off to become parts of Ray and Daviess Counties.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The Mormons chose a site in the town of Far West to build a temple, which was never finished due to the war.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] This arrangement brought about a period of relative peace.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] In 1837, problems centered on the Kirtland Safety Society bank at the church's headquarters in Kirtland, Ohio led to schism.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The church relocated in January 1838 from Kirtland to Far West, Missouri, which became its new headquarters.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Hundreds of Mormon settlers from Kirtland and elsewhere poured into Missouri.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] They established new colonies outside of Caldwell County, including Adam-ondi-Ahman in Daviess County and De Witt in Carroll County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] In the eyes of many non-Mormon citizens (including Alexander Doniphan), these settlements outside of Caldwell County were a violation of the compromise.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The Mormons felt that the compromise only excluded major settlements in Clay and Ray counties, as they already had substantial population centers, but not the recently colonized Daviess and Carroll.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The earlier settlers felt politically and economically threatened by the expanding Mormon communities outside of Caldwell County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] With the Kirtland-based presidency now in control of the Missouri church, a leadership struggle emerged between the Kirtland arrivals and the previously established Missouri church leadership.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Many of the oldest and most prominent leaders of the church, including Oliver Cowdery (one of the Three Witnesses and the church's original "second elder"), David Whitmer (another of the Three Witnesses and Stake President of the Missouri Church), John Whitmer, and William W.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Phelps, were excommunicated on allegations of misusing church property and finance amid tense relations between them and Smith.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] These "dissenters", as they came to be called, owned a significant amount of land in Caldwell County, much of which they purchased when acting as agents of the church.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Ownership became unclear and the dissenters threatened the church with lawsuits.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The presidency responded by urging the dissenters to leave the county using strong words the dissenters interpreted as threats.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] In his famous Salt Sermon, Sidney Rigdon announced that the dissenters were as salt that had lost its savor and that it was the duty of the faithful to cast the dissenters out to be trodden beneath the feet of men.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] At the same time, Sampson Avard led a group of Mormons to organize a vigilante body known as the Danites.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On July 4, Rigdon gave an oration characterized by Mormon historian Brigham Henry Roberts as a "'Declaration of Independence' from all mobs and persecutions".
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The text of this speech was endorsed by Joseph Smith, who appeared at the event and participated in the raising of a liberty pole.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Newly-formed Daviess County, Missouri, held its first elections on August 6, 1838.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] William Peniston, a candidate for the state legislature, referred to the Mormons as "horse-thieves and robbers" and warned them not to vote in the election.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] When about thirty Mormons approached the polling place, a Missourian named Dick Weldon declared that in Clay County the Mormons had been allowed to vote "no more than the negroes".
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] One of the Mormons present, Samuel Brown, claimed that the statement was false and then declared his intention to vote.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] This triggered a brawl between the bystanders.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] At the start of the brawl, Mormon John Butler let out a call, "Oh yes, you Danites, here is a job for us!" which rallied the Mormons and allowed them to drive off their opponents.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The crowd dispersed and the Mormons returned to their homes.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] This skirmish is often cited as the first episode of serious violence of the Mormon War.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Rumor among both parties held that the conflict resulted in casualties.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] However, when Joseph Smith rode with volunteers to Daviess County to assess the situation, he discovered there was no truth to this.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Non-Mormons began to organize themselves into vigilance committees.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] When a rumor reached the Mormons that Judge Adam Black was gathering a mob near Millport, Joseph Smith sent Danite leaders Sampson Avrard, Cornelius Lott and Lyman Wight to his home.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] They surrounded it with one hundred armed men, including Smith's cousin George A.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] They asked if this was true, demanding that he sign a document disavowing any connection to the vigilance committees.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] At a meeting at Lyman Wight's home between leading Mormons and non-Mormons, both sides agreed not to protect any law-breakers and to surrender all offenders to the authorities.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] With peace restored, Smith's group returned to Caldwell County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Black later swore an affidavit before the justice of the peace in Daviess county attesting to the treatment and threats he received from George Smith the other church members.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On September 7, Smith and Lyman Wight appeared before Judge Austin A.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Three Danite leaders testified convincingly in their defence.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] George Robinson asserted that evidence of wrongdoing was insufficient.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] However Judge King ordered Smith and Wight to stand trial in order to pacify the mob.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] In the spring of 1838, Henry Root, a non-Mormon and a major landowner in Carroll County, visited Far West and sold his plots in the mostly vacant town of De Witt to Mormons he had invited there.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] De Witt was strategically located near the confluence of the Grand and the Missouri Rivers.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Hinkle and John Murdock, members of the High Council at Far West, were sent to take possession of the town and to begin to colonize it.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On July 30, citizens of Carroll County met in Carrollton to discuss this.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The question of whether or not Mormons should be allowed to settle in the county was placed on the August 6 ballot; a heavy majority favored expulsion of the Mormons.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] A committee sent to De Witt ordered the Mormons to leave.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The Mormon leaders refused, citing their right as American citizens to settle where they pleased.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Sentiment among the anti-Mormon segment of Carroll County's population hardened, and some began to take up arms.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On August 19, 1838, Mormon settler Smith Humphrey reported that 100 armed men led by Colonel William Claude Jones took him prisoner for two hours and threatened him and the rest of the Mormon community.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] As tensions built in Daviess County, other counties began to respond to Carroll County's request for assistance in expelling the Mormons from their midst.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Citizens in Saline, Howard, Jackson, Chariton, Ray, and other nearby counties organized vigilance committees sympathetic to the Carroll County expulsion party.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Some isolated Mormons in outlying areas also came under attack.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] In Livingston County, a group of armed men forced Asahel Lathrop from his home, where they held his family captive while they were sick.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Lathrop's wife and remaining children died shortly after their rescue.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On September 20, 1838, about one hundred fifty armed men rode into De Witt and demanded that the Mormons leave within ten days.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Hinkle and other Mormon leaders informed the men that they would fight.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] They also sent a request for assistance to Governor Boggs, noting that the mob had threatened "to exterminate them, without regard to age or sex".
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On October 1, vigilantes burned the home and stables of Smith Humphrey.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Later that day, the vigilantes sealed off the town.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The besieged town resorted to butchering whatever loose livestock wandered into town in order to avoid starvation while waiting for the militia or the Governor to come to their aid.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] General Parks arrived with the Ray County militia on October 6, but his order to disperse was ignored.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] When his own troops threatened to join the attackers, Parks was forced to withdraw to Daviess County in hopes that the Governor would come to mediate.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Caldwell returned to De Witt with the Governor's response: "the quarrel was between the Mormons and the mob" and they should fight it out.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On October 11, Mormon leaders agreed to abandon the settlement and move to Caldwell County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On the first night of the march out of Carroll County two Mormon women died, one of exposure and the other, a woman named Jenson, in childbirth.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Several children also became ill during the ordeal and died later.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Boggs, however, ignored this plea as events unravelled.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Meanwhile, a group of vigilantes from Clinton, Platte, and other counties began to harass Mormons in Daviess County, burning outlying homes and plundering property.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Latter Day Saint refugees began to flee to Adam-ondi-Ahman for protection and shelter against the upcoming winter.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] As Joseph Smith returned to Far West in Caldwell County from De Witt in Carroll County to the west General Doniphan informed him of the deteriorating situation.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Doniphan already had raised troops to prevent fighting between Mormons and those opposed to them in Daviess County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On Sunday, October 14, a small company of state militia under the command of Colonel William A.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Dunn of Clay County arrived in Far West.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Dunn, acting on Doniphan's orders, continued on to Adam-ondi-Ahman.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Although he was sympathetic to the Mormons' plight, Doniphan reminded the Latter Day Saints that their Caldwell County militia, led by church member Colonel George M.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Hinkle, could not legally enter Daviess County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] He advised Mormons traveling there to go in small parties and unarmed.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Ignoring this counsel, Elias Higbee, a Mormon judge in Caldwell County, called on the Caldwell militia to defend church members' settlements in neighboring Daviess County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] They were joined by elements of the Danite vigilante organization.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On October 18, these two groups marched under arms in three groups to Daviess County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Lyman Wight attacked Millport, and David W.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Patten attacked Gallatin, both of which had been evacuated before they arrived.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Seymour Brunson attacked Grindstone Fork, driving the unarmed Missourians from their homes to make their way to neighboring counties.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Having taken control of the Missourian settlements, the Mormons plundered the property and burned the stores and houses.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The county seat, Gallatin, was reported to have been "completely gutted" – only one shoe store remained unscathed.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Millport, Grindstone Fork and the smaller Missourian settlement of Splawn's Ridge were also plundered and had some houses burned.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The plundered goods were deposited in the Bishop's storehouse at Diahman.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] During the days that followed, Mormon vigilantes under the direction of Lyman Wight drove Missourians who lived in outlying farms from their homes, which were similarly plundered and burned.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] According to one witness, "We could stand in our door and see houses burning every night for over two weeks... the Mormons completely gutted Daviess County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] There was scarcely a Missourian's home left standing in the county.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The Missourians evicted from their homes were no better prepared than the Mormon refugees had been.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] After the stress of being expelled from Millport into the snow, Milford Donaho's wife gave birth prematurely, and the child was severely injured during the birth.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Even Missourians who had been friendly to the Mormons were not spared.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Jacob Stollings, a Gallatin merchant, was reported to have been generous in selling to Mormons on credit, but his store was plundered and burned with the rest.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Judge Josiah Morin and Samuel McBrier, both considered friendly to the Mormons, both fled Daviess County after being threatened.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] When a Mormon band plundered and burned the Taylor home, one young Mormon, Benjamin F Johnson, argued his fellow vigilantes into leaving a horse for a pregnant Mrs Taylor and her children to ride to safety.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Ironically, as a result of his kindness, he was the only Mormon who was positively identified to have participated in the home burnings.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] After several non-Mormons made statements to the authorities that Johnson had acted as a moderating influence on the Danites, he was allowed to escape rather than stand trial.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Many Latter Day Saints were greatly troubled by the occurrences.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Mormon leader John Corrill wrote, "the love of pillage grew upon them very fast, for they plundered every kind of property they could get a hold of." Some Mormons claimed that some of the Missourians burned their own homes in order to blame the Mormons.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] None of these claims, however, purport to be eyewitness accounts.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] These claims are contradicted by the majority of both Missourian and Latter Day Saint testimony and also by the evidence of the looted property found in the possession of Latter Day Saints.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Mormon leader Parley P Pratt conceded that some burnings had been done by Mormons.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] LeSueur estimates that Mormons were responsible for the burning of fifty homes or shops and the displacement of one hundred non-Mormon families.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Millport, which at time was the largest settlement in the county and the center for trade, never recovered from the Mormon burnings, and became a ghost town.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Local citizens were outraged by the actions of the Danites and other Mormon bands.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Several Mormon homes near Millport were burned and their inhabitants expelled into the snow.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Agnes Smith, a sister-in-law of Joseph, was chased from her home with two small children when her home was burned.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] With one child in each arm, she waded across an icy creek to safety in Adam-ondi-Ahman.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Nathan Tanner reported that his militia company rescued another woman and three small children who were hiding in the bushes as their home burned.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Other Mormons, fearing similar retribution by the Missourians, gathered into Adam-ondi-Ahman for protection.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Marsh, President of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles of the church, and fellow Apostle Orson Hyde were alarmed by the events of the Daviess County expedition.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On October 19, 1838, the day after Gallatin was burned, Thomas B.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Marsh and fellow apostle Orson Hyde left the association of the Church.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On October 24, they swore out affidavits concerning the burning and looting in Daviess County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] They also reported the existence of the Danite group among the Mormons and repeated a popular rumor that a group of Danites was planning to attack and burn Richmond and Liberty.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Fearing attack, many citizens of Ray County moved their wives and children across the Missouri River for safety.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] A militia under the command of Samuel Bogart was authorized by General Atchison to patrol the no-man's land between Ray and Caldwell Counties known as "Bunkham's Strip" – a territory 6 miles (9.7 km) east to west and 1-mile (1.6 km) north to south.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Instead of staying in the strip, Bogart crossed into Caldwell County and began to disarm Mormons, reportedly threatening to attack Far West.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] When rumors reached Far West that a mob had taken Mormons prisoner and were threatening to execute them, an armed party was quickly assembled to rescue these prisoners and drive the mob out of the county.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] When the Mormons arrived on the scene, the militia was camped along Crooked River in the Bunkham's Strip just south of Caldwell County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] After a militia sentry shot at the crowd, the Mormons divided into three columns led by David W.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The militia broke ranks and fled across the river.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Although Mormons won the battle, they took heavier casualties than the militia, only one of whom, Moses Rowland, was killed.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On the Mormon side, Gideon Carter was killed in the battle and nine other Mormons were wounded, including Patten, who soon after died from his wounds.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] According to one Mormon witness, the deaths "threw a gloom over the whole place".
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] News of the battle quickly spread and contributed to an all-out panic in northwestern Missouri.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Exaggerated initial reports indicated that nearly all of Bogart's company had been killed.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Generals Atchison, Doniphon and Parks decided they needed to call out the militia to "prevent further violence".
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Missouri vigilantes continued to act on their own, driving Mormons inward to Far West and Adam-ondi-Ahman.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Meanwhile, exaggerated reports from the Battle of Crooked River made their way to Missouri's governor, Lilburn Boggs.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Boggs was considered more adversarial towards the Mormons than his predecessor, and, as Lieutenant Governor, had sided with the vigilantes who had expelled the Mormons from Jackson County in 1833.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Boggs mustered 2,500 state militiamen to put down what he considered a Mormon insurrection against the state.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Agitation against the Latter Day Saints had become particularly fierce in the sparsely settled counties north and east of Caldwell County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Mormon dissenters from Daviess County who had fled to Livingston County reportedly told Livingston County militia under Colonel Thomas Jennings that Mormons were gathering at Hawn's Mill to mount a raid into Livingston County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Although it had just been issued, little evidence exists that the governor's "Extermination Order" had reached the attackers.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] None of the participants in the raid cited the order as justification for their actions.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On October 29, this large vigilante band of about 250 men assembled and entered eastern Caldwell County.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] When the Missourian raiders approached the settlement on the afternoon of October 30, some 30 to 40 Latter Day Saint families were living or encamped there.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Despite an attempt by the Mormons to parley, the mob attacked.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Thomas McBride surrendered his rifle to Jacob Rogers, who shot McBride with his own gun.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] When McBride held out a hand, Rogers cut it off with a corn knife, then may have further mangled his body while McBride was still alive.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Other members of the mob opened fire, which sent the Mormons fleeing in all directions.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] While Mormon women and children scattered and hid in the surrounding woods and nearby homes, Mormon men and boys rallied to defend the settlement.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] They moved into a blacksmith shop, which they hoped to use as a makeshift defensive fortification.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] However, the shop had large gaps between the logs which the Missourians shot into and, as one Mormon later recalled, it became more "slaughter-house rather than a shelter".
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] After firing at the shop for half an hour, some of the Missourians entered to kill the survivors.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] They found 10-year-old Sardius Smith hiding behind the bellows.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] William Reynolds of Livingston County shot and killed the boy, saying: "Nits will make lice, and if he had lived he would have become a Mormon" 17 were killed in total.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] When survivors of the massacre reached Far West, the reports of the savagery of the attack played a significant part in the decision of the Mormons to surrender.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] No Missourians were ever prosecuted for their role in the Hawn's Mill Massacre.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Most Mormons gathered to Far West and Adam-ondi-Ahman for protection.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Lucas marched the state militia to Far West and laid siege to the Mormon headquarters on 1 November.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Surrounded by the state militia, Joseph Smith ordered Colonel George M.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Hinkle, the head of the Mormon militia in Caldwell County, to ride out and meet with General Lucas to seek terms.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] According to Hinkle, Smith wanted a treaty with the Missourians "on any terms short of battle".
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Other Latter Day Saint witnesses remembered that Smith said to "beg like a dog for peace".
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The Mormons were to give up their leaders for trial and to surrender all of their arms.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Every Mormon who had taken up arms was to sell his property to pay for the damages to Missourian property and for the muster of the state militia.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Finally, the Mormons who had taken up arms were to leave the state.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Colonel Hinkle stated that the Mormons would help bring to justice those who had violated the law, but he protested that the other terms were illegal and unconstitutional.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Colonel Hinkle rode to the church leaders in Far West and informed them of the offered terms.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] According to Mormon witness Reed Peck, when Smith was told that the Mormons would be expected to leave the state, he replied that "he did not care" and that he would be glad to get out of the "damnable state" anyway.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Smith and the other leaders rode with Hinkle back to the Missouri militia encampment.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The militia promptly arrested Smith and the other leaders.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Smith believed that Hinkle had betrayed him, but Hinkle maintained his innocence and claimed that he was following Smith's orders.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Joseph Smith and the other arrested leaders were held overnight under guard in General Lucas' camp.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Hyrum Smith, Brigham Young, and other leaders left at Far West warned the veterans of Crooked River to flee.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] "If found, they will be shot down like dogs," warned Hyrum.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Joseph Smith attempted to negotiate with Lucas, but Lucas considered his conditions to be non-negotiable.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] At 8:00 am, Joseph sent word to Far West to surrender.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The Far West militia was marched out of the city and forced to turn over their weapons to General Lucas.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The men under the command of Lucas were then allowed to ransack the city to search for weapons.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Lucas tried Joseph Smith and other Mormon leaders by court martial on November 1, the evening of the surrender.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The defendants, consisting of about 60 men including Joseph Smith and Sidney Rigdon, were turned over to a civil court of inquiry in Richmond under Judge Austin A.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] King, on charges of treason, murder, arson, burglary, robbery, larceny and perjury.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The court of inquiry began November 12, 1838.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] After the inquiry, most of the Mormon prisoners were released, but Joseph Smith, Sidney Rigdon, Lyman Wight, Caleb Baldwin, Hyrum Smith and Alexander McRae were held in the Liberty Jail in Liberty, Clay County on charges of treason against the state, murder, arson, burglary, robbery and larceny.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] During a transfer to another prison in the spring of 1839, Smith and the other prisoners escaped.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The exact circumstances that allowed for him to escape are not certain.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] John Whitmer suggests that Smith bribed the guards.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Historian Richard Bushman believes that Smith's imprisonment had become an embarrassment, and that an escape would be convenient for Boggs and the rest of the Missouri political establishment.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Smith and the other Mormons resettled in Nauvoo, Illinois, beginning in 1839.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Daviess County residents were outraged by the escape of Smith and the other leaders.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] William Bowman, one of the guards, was dragged by his hair across the town square.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Sheriff Morgan was ridden through town on an iron bar, and died shortly afterward from the injuries he suffered during the ride.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] General Clark viewed Executive Order 44 as having been fulfilled by the agreement of the Mormons to evacuate the state the following spring.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The militia was disbanded in late November.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Missouri blamed the Mormons for the conflict and forced the Mormons to sign over all their lands in order to pay for the state militia muster.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Mormon leaders appealed to the state legislature to overturn the requirement that they leave the state, but the legislature tabled the issue until a date well after that when the Mormons would have left the state.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Having surrendered the bulk of their firearms, Mormons were left nearly defenseless against the mobs.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Mormon residents were harassed and attacked by angry residents who were no longer restrained by militia officers.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Stripped of their property, most refugees made their way east to Illinois, where residents of the town of Quincy helped them.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] When faced with the Mormon refugees from Missouri, the people of Quincy were outraged by the treatment the Mormons had experienced.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Eventually, the Mormons purchased and settled the mostly vacant city of Commerce, north of Quincy, which they renamed Nauvoo in 1839.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Many of Boggs's constituents felt that he had mismanaged the situation by failing to intervene earlier in the crisis, and then by overreacting on the basis of partial and incorrect information.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Even people who otherwise expressed no sympathy towards the Mormons disapproved of Boggs's order and the treatment of the Mormons by the mobs.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] LeSueur notes that, along with other setbacks, Boggs's mishandling of the Mormon conflict left him "politically impotent" by the end of his term.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On May 6, 1842, Boggs was shot in the head at his home three blocks from Temple Lot.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Boggs survived, but Mormons came under immediate suspicion, especially Orrin Porter Rockwell, bodyguard of Joseph Smith.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Reynolds discovered a revolver at the scene, still loaded with buckshot.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] He surmised that the perpetrator had fired upon Boggs and lost his firearm in the night when the weapon recoiled due to its unusually large shot.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The gun was found to have been stolen from a local shopkeeper, who identified "that hired man of Ward's" as the most likely culprit.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Reynolds determined the man in question was Rockwell.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Bennett, a disaffected Mormon, reported that Smith had offered a cash reward to anyone who would assassinate Boggs, and that Smith had admitted to him that Rockwell had done the deed.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Joseph Smith denied Bennett's account, speculating that Boggs—who was campaigning for state senate—was attacked by an election opponent.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] One historian notes that Governor Boggs was running for election against several violent men, all capable of the deed, and that there was no particular reason to suspect Rockwell of the crime.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Other historians are convinced that Rockwell was involved in the shooting.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The following year, Rockwell was arrested, tried, and acquitted of the attempted murder, after a grand jury was unable to find sufficient evidence to indict him, although most of Boggs' contemporaries remained convinced of his guilt.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Rockwell famously stated that he "never shot *at* anybody, if I shoot they get shot!...
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Mormons reported threats of sexual violence, attempts to commit it and actual acts of rape perpetrated on Mormon women.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Ruth Napier (whose husband William was killed in the massacre) swore before a justice of the peace that, in early November, after the Haun's Mill Massacre, armed non-Mormons billeted themselves in her home without her consent while she was living there as a widow with small children.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] One night as she was sleeping one of the men came to her bed and fondled her.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] She was so frightened she made some sort of commotion and crawled over her children to get away.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] He retreated and tried nothing more that night.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Elijah Reed similarly swore before a clerk of the circuit court that, fleeing for his life from a group of armed Missouri settlers, he took shelter with the Jameson family (here spelled "Jimmison").
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] On October 29, a group of Missourians came to the house, demanding entrance or they would break down the door.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Jimmison answered the door while Reed hid under a bed.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The men, identifying themselves as soldiers, said they had come to take Mr.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] As Jimmison was taken to get a horse for him to ride away with them, he broke free and escaped.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] They returned to the house and began to assault Mrs.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Jimmison, preparing to rape her as Reed witnessed this from under the bed.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] According to Reed, they stopped fondling her after she cried and begged for them to do so.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Hyrum Smith stated under oath before a municipal judge that after the skirmishes that destroyed houses and farmlands, the Mormon leadership sent a message to General Atchison and expected an army to provide protection for them.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The army that arrived the evening of October 30 was led by General Doniphan and the far less friendly General Lucas, who had already murdered Mormons in the area in 1833 and 1834.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The next day the Mormon leaders and men of Far West were lured to a cornfield on the pretext of a consultation with the generals and officers but they were surrounded and taken prisoner.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] November 1, the armed soldiers patrolling the streets of Far West were permitted enter homes, molest the people at their leisure, confiscate the firearms and ravish (rape) the women there.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] Pratt attested before a municipal judge that he was among the group with Joseph Smith who were taken prisoner in the corn field.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] He said that while imprisoned, their guards named a couple of female Mormons and claimed that about twenty or thirty soldiers had tied the women down and raped them.
[src:bible/1838-mormon-war] The account John Murdock recorded in his journal reflects what Pratt and Smith avowed, adding that the rapes and abuse continued for as long as the Mormons remained in Missouri.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] The **1890 Manifesto** (also known as the **Woodruff Manifesto**, the **Anti-polygamy Manifesto**, or simply "**the Manifesto**") is a statement which officially advised against any future plural marriage in the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Upon its issuance, the LDS Church in conference accepted Woodruff's Manifesto as "authoritative and binding".
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] The Manifesto was a dramatic turning point in the history of the LDS Church.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] It advised church members against entering into any marriage prohibited by the law of the land, and made it easier for Utah to become a U.S. state.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Nevertheless, even after the Manifesto, the church quietly continued to perform a small number of plural marriages in the United States, Mexico, and Canada, thus necessitating a Second Manifesto during U.S. congressional hearings in 1904.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Though neither Manifesto dissolved existing plural marriages, plural marriage in the LDS Church gradually died by attrition during the early-to-mid 20th century.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Some Mormon fundamentalists rejected the manifesto.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] The Manifesto was issued in response to the anti-polygamy policies of the federal government of the United States, and most especially the Edmunds–Tucker Act of 1887.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] This law disincorporated the LDS Church and authorized the federal government to seize all of the church's assets.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Supreme Court upheld the provisions of the Edmunds–Tucker Act in *Late Corporation of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints v.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] In April 1889, Woodruff, the president of the church, began privately refusing the permission that was required to contract new plural marriages.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] In October 1889, Woodruff publicly admitted that he was no longer approving new polygamous marriages, and in answer to a reporter's question of what the LDS Church's attitude was toward the law against polygamy, Woodruff stated, "We mean to obey it.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] We have no thought of evading it or ignoring it." Because it had been Mormon practice for over 25 years to either evade or ignore anti-polygamy laws, Woodruff's statement was a signal that a change in church policy was developing.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] In February 1890, the Supreme Court ruled in *Davis v.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Beason* that a law in Idaho Territory which disenfranchised individuals who practiced or believed in plural marriage was constitutional.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] That decision left the Mormons no further legal recourse to their current marriage practices and made it unlikely that without change Utah Territory would be granted statehood.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Woodruff later said that on the night of September 23, 1890, he received a revelation from Jesus Christ that the church should cease the practice of plural marriage.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] The following morning, he reported this to some of the general authorities and placed the hand-written draft on a table.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] George Reynolds would later recount that he, Charles W.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Winder modified Woodruff's draft into the current language accepted by the general authorities and presented to the church as a whole.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Woodruff announced the Manifesto on September 25 by publishing it in the church-owned *Deseret Weekly* in Salt Lake City.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] On October 6, 1890, it was formally accepted by the church membership, though many held reservations or abstained from voting.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Utah ratified its constitution in November 1895 and was granted statehood on January 4, 1896.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] One of the conditions for granting Utah statehood was that a ban on polygamy be written into its state constitution.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Less than a month after the Manifesto was issued, the LDS Church used the procedure of common consent to make it binding upon church members.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] The Manifesto was the end of official church authorization for the creation of new plural marriages that violated local laws.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] It had no effect on the status of already existing plural marriages, and plural marriages continued to be performed in locations where it was believed to be legal.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] As Woodruff explained at the general conference where the Manifesto was accepted by the church, "[t]his Manifesto only refers to future marriages, and does not affect past conditions.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] I did not, I could not, and would not promise that you would desert your wives and children.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] This you cannot do in honor." Despite Woodruff's explanation, some church leaders and members who were polygamous did begin to live with only one wife.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] However, the majority of Mormon polygamists continued to cohabit with their plural wives in violation of the Edmunds Act.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Within six years of the announcement of the Manifesto, Utah had become a state and federal prosecution of Mormon polygamists subsided.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] However, Congress still refused to seat representatives-elect who were polygamists, including B.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Michael Quinn and other Mormon historians have documented that some church apostles covertly sanctioned plural marriages after the Manifesto.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] This practice was especially prevalent in Mexico and Canada because of an erroneous belief that such marriages were legal in those jurisdictions.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] However, a significant minority were performed in Utah and other western American states and territories.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] The estimates of the number of post-Manifesto plural marriages performed range from scores to thousands, with the actual figure probably close to 250.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Rumors of post-Manifesto marriages surfaced and began to be examined by Congress in the Reed Smoot hearings.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Smith issued a "Second Manifesto" in 1904 which reaffirmed the church's opposition to the creation of new plural marriages and threatened excommunication for Latter-day Saints who continued to enter into or solemnize new plural marriages.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Cowley both resigned from the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles due to disagreement with the church's position on plural marriage.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Plural marriage in violation of local law continues to be grounds for excommunication from the LDS Church.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] The cessation of plural marriage within LDS Church gave rise to the Mormon fundamentalist movement.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] The Manifesto has been canonized by the LDS Church, and its text appears in the Doctrine and Covenants, one of the church's books of scripture.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] However, when the Manifesto was issued, it was not apparent that Woodruff or the other leaders of the LDS Church viewed it as the result of a divine revelation.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Approximately one year after he declared the Manifesto, Woodruff began to claim that he had received instructions from Jesus Christ that formed the basis of what he wrote in the text of the Manifesto.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] These instructions were reportedly accompanied by a vision of what would occur if the Manifesto were not issued.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Following Woodruff's death in 1898, other church leaders began to teach that the Manifesto was the result of a revelation of God.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] Since that time, church leaders have consistently taught that the Manifesto was inspired of God.
[src:bible/1890-manifesto] In 1908, the Manifesto was printed in the LDS Church's Doctrine and Covenants for the first time, and it has been included in every edition since.
[src:bible/2-baruch] The Letter of Baruch had a separate and wider circulation than the rest of the book, and is attested in thirty-six Syriac manuscripts.
[src:bible/2-baruch] The Apocalypse proper has been less widely available.
[src:bible/2-baruch] One Latin excerpt was known from a quotation in Cyprian.
[src:bible/2-baruch] A 4th–5th century CE Greek fragment was found among the Oxyrhynchus manuscripts.
[src:bible/2-baruch] Two excerpts were known from 13th century lectionaries of the Syriac Orthodox Church.
[src:bible/2-baruch] The full text of 2 Baruch is now known from a 6th or 7th century CE Syriac manuscript discovered by Antonio Ceriani in the Biblioteca Ambrosiana in Milan in 1866.
[src:bible/2-baruch] An Arabic manuscript of the whole text was discovered in 1974.
[src:bible/2-baruch] It is apparently a rather free translation from a Syriac text similar to the Milan manuscript.
[src:bible/2-baruch] Although the canonical Book of Jeremiah portrays Baruch as Jeremiah's scribe, 2 Baruch portrays him as a prophet in his own right.
[src:bible/2-baruch] It has a style similar to the writings attributed to Jeremiah: a mix of prayer, lamentation, and visions.
[src:bible/2-baruch] Although Baruch writes of Nebuchadnezzar's sack of Jerusalem in 586 BCE, the book is currently believed to have been written in reaction to the fall of Jerusalem in 70 CE, but written before 135 CE.
[src:bible/2-baruch] The Syriac is almost certainly a translation from the Greek; the original was probably written in Hebrew.
[src:bible/2-baruch] There is a close relation between the apocalypse described here and that in 2 Esdras, but critics are divided over the question of which influenced the other.
[src:bible/2-baruch] The probabilities favor the hypothesis that that in 2 Baruch is an imitation of that of Esdras and therefore later.
[src:bible/2-baruch] This Apocalypse of Baruch deals in part with the same problems, the sufferings of the theocratic people, and their ultimate triumph over their oppressors.
[src:bible/2-baruch] Its Messianism, in general, is earthly, but in the latter part of the book the Messiah's realm tends unmistakably towards a more spiritual conception.
[src:bible/2-baruch] Greater importance is attached to the law than in the related composition.
[src:bible/2-baruch] Some scholars of 2 Baruch have seen in it a composite work, but the majority of critics consider it unified.
[src:bible/2-baruch] As in 2 Esdras, sin is traced to the disobedience of Adam, but different stances are taken about the hereditary nature of Adam's sin: while 2 Esdras supports it, 2 Baruch has a quite different position: "each of us has been the Adam of his own soul" (54:15).
[src:bible/2-baruch] The first part of the text is structured in triplets: three fasts, each followed by three visions and three addresses to the people.
[src:bible/2-baruch] The visions are notable for their discussion of theodicy, the problem of evil, and an emphasis on predestination.
[src:bible/2-baruch] According to the text, the Temple's sacred objects were rescued from destruction under the protection of angels, to be returned during the restoration prophesied in the Book of Jeremiah.
[src:bible/2-baruch] The second part of the text is a long letter (known as Letter of Baruch), which many scholars believe was originally a separate document.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] The SEC further charged that the forms that were filed by the shell companies deliberately concealed the amount of control that EP had over investment decisions.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] The charges were settled, with the LDS Church paying a $1 million penalty, and EP paying a $4 million penalty.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] In September 2023, the Salt Lake Tribune suggested that the LDS Church may have additionally failed to file disclosure forms for its $9 billion pension and health plan fund.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] In 1963, the LDS Church was on the brink of insolvency, and N.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] Eldon Tanner was brought in to rescue the LDS Church finances.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] Tanner emphasized investing and a disdain for deficit spending, returning the LDS Church finances to sound footing.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] In 1997, the LDS Church split off its investment division and created a separate legal entity called EP.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] Form 13F is a quarterly report filed, per SEC regulations, by "institutional investment managers" with control over $100M in assets to the SEC, listing all equity assets under management.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] The purpose of the form is to provide transparency over who owns stocks.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] LLCs were designed to make it difficult to connect with the LDS Church and EP.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] LLCs were dispersed across geographic locations throughout the United States outside the state of Utah.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] EP granted management authority to a hand-picked manager but retained investment authority and discretion over each LLC.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] The SEC asserts that managers of the LLCs were not given sufficient information to accurately check the box that the form filled out was "true, correct and complete." Several times electronic signatures were forwarded to the SEC by EP before managers provided handwritten signatures.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] Additionally, managers incorrectly misstated that they were signing forms at the location of the LLC's stated address, given that each manager was located in Salt Lake City, Utah.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] Hu, a corporate and securities law professor at the University of Texas law school, stated, "What the law requires is so clear that I am genuinely surprised that anyone would do this" Jacob S.
[src:bible/2023-securities-and-exchange-commission-charges-against-the-church-of-jesus-chri] Frenkel, a former senior counsel in the SEC's division of enforcement, commented in regards to the small size of the fine: "They are showing institutional respect for the church.
[src:bible/bible-p01] A **Bible** is a collection of religious texts that is central to Christianity or Judaism, and esteemed in other Abrahamic religions such as Islam.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Bibles are anthologies (compilations of texts of a variety of forms) with varying canonical texts across traditions.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The Hebrew Bible was originally written in Hebrew (with some parts in Aramaic) and the second portion of the Christian Bible, known as the New Testament, was originally written in Koine Greek.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Biblical texts include instructions, stories, poetry, letters, prophecies, and other genres.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The collection of materials accepted as part of the Bible by a particular religious tradition or community is called a biblical canon.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Believers generally consider it to be a product of divine inspiration, but the way they understand what that means and how they interpret the text varies.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The religious texts, or scriptures, were compiled by different religious communities into various official collections.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The earliest contained the first five books of the Bible, called the Torah ('Teaching') in Hebrew and the Pentateuch (meaning 'five books') in Greek.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The second-oldest part was a collection of narrative histories and prophecies (the Nevi'im).
[src:bible/bible-p01] The third collection, the Ketuvim, contains psalms, proverbs, and narrative histories.
[src:bible/bible-p01] *Tanakh* (Hebrew: תָּנָ״ךְ‎, romanized: **Tanaḵ**) is an alternate term for the Hebrew Bible.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The Masoretic Text is the medieval version of the Tanakh—written in Hebrew and Aramaic—that is considered the authoritative text of the Hebrew Bible by modern Rabbinic Judaism.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The Septuagint is a Koine Greek translation of the Tanakh from the third and second centuries BCE; it largely overlaps with the Hebrew Bible.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Christianity began as an outgrowth of Second Temple Judaism, using the Septuagint as the basis of the first portion of the Christian Bible, known as the Old Testament.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The early Church continued the Jewish tradition of writing and incorporating what it saw as inspired, authoritative religious books.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The gospels, which are narratives about the life and teachings of Jesus, along with the Pauline epistles and other texts quickly coalesced into the New Testament.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The oldest parts of the Bible may be as early as c.
[src:bible/bible-p01] 1200 BCE, while the books of the New Testament were mostly written in the 1st century CE.
[src:bible/bible-p01] With estimated total sales of over five billion copies, the Christian Bible is the best-selling publication of all time.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Biblical texts have had a profound influence both on Western culture and history and on cultures around the globe.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The study of these texts through biblical criticism has also indirectly impacted culture and history.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Some view biblical texts as morally problematic, historically inaccurate, or corrupted by time; others find it a useful historical source for certain peoples and events or a source of ethical teachings.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The Christian Bible is currently translated or in the process of being translated into about half of the world's languages.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The term *Bible* can refer to the Hebrew Bible, which corresponds to the Christian Old Testament, or the Christian Bible, which in addition to the Old Testament contains the New Testament.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The English word *Bible* is derived from Koine Greek: τὰ βιβλία, romanized: *ta biblia*, meaning 'the books' (singular βιβλίον, *biblion*).
[src:bible/bible-p01] The word βιβλίον itself literally means 'scroll' and came to be used as the ordinary word for *book*.
[src:bible/bible-p01] It is the diminutive of βύβλος *byblos*, 'Egyptian papyrus', possibly so called from the name of the Phoenician seaport Byblos (also known as Gebal) whence Egyptian papyri would be exported to Greece.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The Greek *ta biblia* was "an expression Hellenistic Jews used to describe their sacred books".
[src:bible/bible-p01] Bruce notes that John Chrysostom appears to be the first writer (in his *Homilies on Matthew*, delivered between 386 and 388 CE) to use the Greek phrase *ta biblia* ('the books') to describe both the Old and New Testaments together.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The Latin *biblia sacra* ('holy books') is a translation of the Greek τὰ βιβλία τὰ ἅγια (*tà biblía tà hágia)*, which also means 'the holy books'.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Medieval Latin *biblia* is short for *biblia sacra* 'holy book'.
[src:bible/bible-p01] It gradually came to be regarded as a feminine singular noun (*biblia*, gen.
[src:bible/bible-p01] *bibliae*) in medieval Latin, and so the word was loaned as singular into the vernaculars of Western Europe.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The complex development of the various texts that make up the Bible is still not completely understood.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The oldest books began as songs and stories orally transmitted from generation to generation.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Scholars of the twenty-first century are only in the beginning stages of exploring "the interface between writing, performance, memorization, and the aural dimension" of the texts.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Current indications are that writing and orality were not separate as much as ancient writing was learned in communal oral performance.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The Bible was written and compiled by many people, who many scholars say are mostly unknown, from a variety of disparate cultures and backgrounds.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The books of the Bible were initially written and copied by hand on papyrus scrolls.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The age of the original composition of the texts is, therefore, difficult to determine and heavily debated.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Using a combined linguistic and historiographical approach, Hendel and Joosten date the oldest parts of the Hebrew Bible (the Song of Deborah in Judges 5 and the Samson story of Judges 16 and 1 Samuel) to having been composed in the premonarchial early Iron Age (c.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The Dead Sea Scrolls, discovered in the caves of Qumran in 1947, are copies that can be dated to between 250 BCE and 100 CE.
[src:bible/bible-p01] They are the oldest existing copies of the books of the Hebrew Bible of any length that are not fragments.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The earliest manuscripts were probably written in paleo-Hebrew, a kind of cuneiform pictograph similar to other pictographs of the same period.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The exile to Babylon most likely prompted the shift to square script (Aramaic) in the fifth to third centuries BCE.
[src:bible/bible-p01] From the time of the Dead Sea Scrolls, the Hebrew Bible was written with spaces between words to aid reading.
[src:bible/bible-p01] By the eighth century CE, the Masoretes added vowel signs.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Levites or scribes maintained the texts, and some texts were always treated as more authoritative than others.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Scribes preserved and changed the texts by changing the script, updating archaic forms, and making corrections.
[src:bible/bible-p01] These Hebrew texts were copied with great care.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Considered to be scriptures (sacred, authoritative religious texts), the books were compiled by different religious communities into various biblical canons (official collections of scriptures).
[src:bible/bible-p01] The earliest compilation, containing the first five books of the Bible and called the Torah (meaning "law", "instruction", or "teaching") or Pentateuch ("five books"), was accepted as Jewish canon by the fifth century BCE.
[src:bible/bible-p01] A second collection of narrative histories and prophesies, called the Nevi'im ("prophets"), was canonized in the third century BCE.
[src:bible/bible-p01] A third collection called the Ketuvim ("writings"), containing psalms, proverbs, and narrative histories, was canonized sometime between the second century BCE and the second century CE.
[src:bible/bible-p01] These three collections were written mostly in Biblical Hebrew, with some parts in Aramaic, which together form the Hebrew Bible or "TaNaKh" (an abbreviation of "Torah", "Nevi'im", and "Ketuvim").
[src:bible/bible-p01] There are three major historical versions of the Hebrew Bible: the Septuagint, the Masoretic Text, and the Samaritan Pentateuch (which contains only the first five books).
[src:bible/bible-p01] They are related but do not share the same paths of development.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Probably commissioned by Ptolemy II Philadelphus, King of Egypt, it addressed the need of the primarily Greek-speaking Jews of the Graeco-Roman diaspora.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Existing complete copies of the Septuagint date from the third to the fifth centuries CE, with fragments dating back to the second century BCE.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Revision of its text began as far back as the first century BCE.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Fragments of the Septuagint were found among the Dead Sea Scrolls; portions of its text are also found on existing papyrus from Egypt dating to the second and first centuries BCE and to the first century CE.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The Masoretes began developing what would become the authoritative Hebrew and Aramaic text of the 24 books of the Hebrew Bible in Rabbinic Judaism near the end of the Talmudic period (c.
[src:bible/bible-p01] 500 CE), but the actual date is difficult to determine.
[src:bible/bible-p01] In the sixth and seventh centuries, three Jewish communities contributed systems for writing the precise letter-text, with its vocalization and accentuation known as the *mas'sora* (from which we derive the term "masoretic").
[src:bible/bible-p01] These early Masoretic scholars were based primarily in the Galilean cities of Tiberias and Jerusalem and in Babylonia (modern Iraq).
[src:bible/bible-p01] Those living in the Jewish community of Tiberias in ancient Galilee (c.
[src:bible/bible-p01] 750–950) made scribal copies of the Hebrew Bible texts without a standard text, such as the Babylonian tradition had, to work from.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The canonical pronunciation of the Hebrew Bible (called Tiberian Hebrew) that they developed, and many of the notes they made, therefore, differed from the Babylonian.
[src:bible/bible-p01] These differences were resolved into a standard text called the Masoretic text in the ninth century.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The oldest complete copy still in existence is the Leningrad Codex dating to c.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The Samaritan Pentateuch is a version of the Torah maintained by the Samaritan community since antiquity, which European scholars rediscovered in the 17th century; its oldest extant copies date to c.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Samaritans include only the Pentateuch (Torah) in their biblical canon.
[src:bible/bible-p01] They do not recognize divine authorship or inspiration in any other book in the Jewish Tanakh.
[src:bible/bible-p01] A Samaritan Book of Joshua partly based upon the Tanakh's Book of Joshua exists, but Samaritans regard it as a non-canonical secular historical chronicle.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The first codex form of the Hebrew Bible was produced in the seventh century.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The codex is the forerunner of the modern book.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Popularized by early Christians, it was made by folding a single sheet of papyrus in half, forming "pages".
[src:bible/bible-p01] Assembling multiples of these folded pages together created a "book" that was more easily accessible and more portable than scrolls.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The first complete printed press version of the Hebrew Bible was produced in 1488.
[src:bible/bible-p01] During the rise of Christianity in the first century CE, new scriptures were written in Koine Greek.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Christians eventually called these new scriptures the "New Testament" and began referring to the Septuagint as the "Old Testament".
[src:bible/bible-p01] The New Testament has been preserved in more manuscripts than any other ancient work.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Most early Christian copyists were not trained scribes.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Many copies of the gospels and Paul's letters were made by individual Christians over a relatively short period of time, very soon after the originals were written.
[src:bible/bible-p01] There is evidence in the Synoptic Gospels, in the writings of the early Church Fathers, from Marcion, and in the Didache that Christian documents were in circulation before the end of the first century.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Paul's letters were circulated during his lifetime, and his death is thought to have occurred before 68 during Nero's reign.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Early Christians transported these writings around the Empire, translating them into Old Syriac, Coptic, Ethiopic, and Latin, and other languages.
[src:bible/bible-p01] These differing histories produced what modern scholars refer to as recognizable "text types".
[src:bible/bible-p01] The four most commonly recognized are Alexandrian, Western, Caesarean, and Byzantine.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The list of books included in the Catholic Bible was established as canon by the Council of Rome in 382, followed by those of Hippo in 393 and Carthage in 397.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Between 385 and 405 CE, the early Christian church translated its canon into Vulgar Latin (the common Latin spoken by ordinary people), a translation known as the Vulgate.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Since then, Catholic Christians have held ecumenical councils to standardize their biblical canon.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The Council of Trent (1545–63), held by the Catholic Church in response to the Protestant Reformation, authorized the Vulgate as its official Latin translation of the Bible.
[src:bible/bible-p01] A number of biblical canons have since evolved.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Christian biblical canons range from the 73 books of the Catholic Church canon and the 66-book canon of most Protestant denominations to the 81 books of the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church canon, among others.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Judaism has long accepted a single authoritative text, whereas Christianity has never had an official version, instead having many different manuscript traditions.
[src:bible/bible-p01] All biblical texts were treated with reverence and care by those who copied them, yet there are transmission errors, called variants, in all biblical manuscripts.
[src:bible/bible-p01] A variant is any deviation between two texts.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Wallace explains, "Each deviation counts as one variant, regardless of how many MSS [manuscripts] attest to it." Hebrew scholar Emanuel Tov says the term is not evaluative; it is a recognition that the paths of development of different texts have separated.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Medieval handwritten manuscripts of the Hebrew Bible were considered extremely precise: the most authoritative documents from which to copy other texts.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Even so, Hebrew Bible scholar David Carr asserts that Hebrew texts still contain some variants.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The majority of all variants are accidental, such as spelling errors, but some changes were intentional.
[src:bible/bible-p01] In the Hebrew text, "memory variants" are generally accidental differences evidenced by such things as the shift in word order found in 1 Chronicles 17:24 and 2 Samuel 10:9 and 13.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Variants also include the substitution of lexical equivalents, semantic and grammar differences, and larger scale shifts in order, with some major revisions of the Masoretic texts that must have been intentional.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Intentional changes in New Testament texts were made to improve grammar, eliminate discrepancies, harmonize parallel passages, combine and simplify multiple variant readings into one, and for theological reasons.
[src:bible/bible-p01] Waltke observes that one variant for every ten words was noted in the recent critical edition of the Hebrew Bible, the *Biblia Hebraica Stuttgartensia,* leaving 90% of the Hebrew text without variation.
[src:bible/bible-p01] The fourth edition of the United Bible Society's *Greek New Testament* notes variants affecting about 500 out of 6900 words, or about 7% of the text.
[src:bible/bible-p02] However, discerning the themes of some biblical texts can be problematic.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Much of the Bible is in narrative form and in general, biblical narrative refrains from any kind of direct instruction, and in some texts the author's intent is not easy to decipher.
[src:bible/bible-p02] It is left to the reader to determine good and bad, right and wrong, and the path to understanding and practice is rarely straightforward.
[src:bible/bible-p02] God is sometimes portrayed as having a role in the plot, but more often there is little about God's reaction to events, and no mention at all of approval or disapproval of what the characters have done or failed to do.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The writer makes no comment, and the reader is left to infer what they will.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Jewish philosophers Shalom Carmy and David Shatz explain that the Bible "often juxtaposes contradictory ideas, without explanation or apology".
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Hebrew Bible contains assumptions about the nature of knowledge, belief, truth, interpretation, understanding and cognitive processes.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Fox writes that the primary axiom of the book of Proverbs is that "the exercise of the human mind is the necessary and sufficient condition of right and successful behavior in all reaches of life".
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Bible teaches the nature of valid arguments, the nature and power of language, and its relation to reality.
[src:bible/bible-p02] According to Alan Mittleman, professor of Jewish philosophy, the Bible provides patterns of moral reasoning that focus on conduct and character.
[src:bible/bible-p02] In the biblical metaphysic, humans have free will, but it is a relative and restricted freedom.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Beach says that Christian *voluntarism* points to the *will* as the core of the self, and that within human nature, "the core of who we are is defined by what we love".
[src:bible/bible-p02] Natural law is in the Wisdom literature, the Prophets, Romans 1, Acts 17, and the book of Amos (Amos 1:3–2:5), where nations other than Israel are held accountable for their ethical decisions even though they do not know the Hebrew god.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Political theorist Michael Walzer finds politics in the Hebrew Bible in covenant, law, and prophecy, which constitute an early form of *almost* democratic political ethics.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Key elements in biblical criminal justice begin with the belief in God as the source of justice and the judge of all, including those administering justice on earth.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The authoritative Hebrew Bible is taken from the masoretic text (called the Leningrad Codex) which dates from 1008.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Hebrew Bible can therefore sometimes be referred to as the Masoretic Text.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Hebrew Bible is also known by the name Tanakh (Hebrew: תנ"ך‎).
[src:bible/bible-p02] This reflects the threefold division of the Hebrew scriptures, Torah ("Teaching"), Nevi'im ("Prophets") and Ketuvim ("Writings") by using the first letters of each word.
[src:bible/bible-p02] It is not until the Babylonian Talmud (c.
[src:bible/bible-p02] 550 CE) that a listing of the contents of these three divisions of scripture are found.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Tanakh was mainly written in Biblical Hebrew, with some small portions (Ezra 4:8–6:18 and 7:12–26, Jeremiah 10:11, Daniel 2:4–7:28) written in Biblical Aramaic, a language which had become the *lingua franca* for much of the Semitic world.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Torah (תּוֹרָה) is also known as the "Five Books of Moses" or the Pentateuch, meaning "five scroll-cases".
[src:bible/bible-p02] Traditionally these books were considered to have been dictated to Moses by God himself.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Since the 17th century, scholars have viewed the original sources as being the product of multiple anonymous authors while also allowing the possibility that Moses first assembled the separate sources.
[src:bible/bible-p02] There are a variety of hypotheses regarding when and how the Torah was composed, but there is a general consensus that it took its final form during the reign of the Persian Achaemenid Empire (probably 450–350 BCE), or perhaps in the early Hellenistic period (333–164 BCE).
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Hebrew names of the books are derived from the first words in the respective texts.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The first eleven chapters of Genesis provide accounts of the creation (or ordering) of the world and the history of God's early relationship with humanity.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The remaining thirty-nine chapters of Genesis provide an account of God's covenant with the biblical patriarchs Abraham, Isaac and Jacob (also called Israel) and Jacob's children, the "Children of Israel", especially Joseph.
[src:bible/bible-p02] It tells of how God commanded Abraham to leave his family and home in the city of Ur, eventually to settle in the land of Canaan, and how the Children of Israel later moved to Egypt.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The remaining four books of the Torah tell the story of Moses, who lived hundreds of years after the patriarchs.
[src:bible/bible-p02] He leads the Children of Israel from slavery in ancient Egypt to the renewal of their covenant with God at Mount Sinai and their wanderings in the desert until a new generation was ready to enter the land of Canaan.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The commandments in the Torah provide the basis for Jewish religious law.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Tradition states that there are 613 commandments (*taryag mitzvot*).
[src:bible/bible-p02] Nevi'im (Hebrew: נְבִיאִים, romanized: *Nəḇī'īm*, "Prophets") is the second main division of the Tanakh, between the Torah and Ketuvim.
[src:bible/bible-p02] It contains two sub-groups, the Former Prophets (*Nevi'im Rishonim* נביאים ראשונים, the narrative books of Joshua, Judges, Samuel and Kings) and the Latter Prophets (*Nevi'im Aharonim* נביאים אחרונים, the books of Isaiah, Jeremiah and Ezekiel and the Twelve Minor Prophets).
[src:bible/bible-p02] It ends with the conquest of the Kingdom of Israel by the Neo-Assyrian Empire, followed by the conquest of the Kingdom of Judah by the neo-Babylonian Empire and the destruction of the Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Former Prophets are the books Joshua, Judges, Samuel and Kings.
[src:bible/bible-p02] They contain narratives that begin immediately after the death of Moses with the divine appointment of Joshua as his successor, who then leads the people of Israel into the Promised Land, and end with the release from imprisonment of the last king of Judah.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Latter Prophets are Isaiah, Jeremiah, Ezekiel and the Twelve Minor Prophets, counted as a single book.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Ketuvim (in Biblical Hebrew: כְּתוּבִים, romanized: *Kəṯūḇīm* "writings") is the third and final section of the Tanakh.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Ketuvim are believed to have been written under the inspiration of Ruach HaKodesh (the Holy Spirit) but with one level less authority than that of prophecy.
[src:bible/bible-p02] In Masoretic manuscripts (and some printed editions), Psalms, Proverbs and Job are presented in a special two-column form emphasizing their internal parallelism, which was found early in the study of Hebrew poetry.
[src:bible/bible-p02] "Stichs" are the lines that make up a verse "the parts of which lie parallel as to form and content".
[src:bible/bible-p02] Collectively, these three books are known as *Sifrei Emet* (an acronym of the titles in Hebrew, איוב, משלי, תהלים yields *Emet* אמ"ת, which is also the Hebrew for "truth").
[src:bible/bible-p02] Hebrew cantillation is the manner of chanting ritual readings as they are written and notated in the Masoretic Text of the Bible.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Psalms, Job and Proverbs form a group with a "special system" of accenting used only in these three books.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The five relatively short books of Song of Songs, Book of Ruth, the Book of Lamentations, Ecclesiastes, and Book of Esther are collectively known as the *Hamesh Megillot*.
[src:bible/bible-p02] These are the latest books collected and designated as authoritative in the Jewish canon even though they were not complete until the second century CE.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The books of Esther, Daniel, Ezra-Nehemiah and Chronicles share a distinctive style that no other Hebrew literary text, biblical or extra-biblical, shares.
[src:bible/bible-p02] They were not written in the normal style of Hebrew of the post-exilic period.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The authors of these books must have chosen to write in their own distinctive style for unknown reasons.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The following list presents the books of Ketuvim in the order they appear in most current printed editions.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Jewish textual tradition never finalized the order of the books in Ketuvim.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Babylonian Talmud (Bava Batra 14b–15a) gives their order as Ruth, Psalms, Job, Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, Song of Solomon, Lamentations of Jeremiah, Daniel, Scroll of Esther, Ezra, Chronicles.
[src:bible/bible-p02] One of the large scale differences between the Babylonian and the Tiberian biblical traditions is the order of the books.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Isaiah is placed after Ezekiel in the Babylonian, while Chronicles opens the Ketuvim in the Tiberian, and closes it in the Babylonian.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Ketuvim is the last of the three portions of the Tanakh to have been accepted as canonical.
[src:bible/bible-p02] While the Torah may have been considered canon by Israel as early as the fifth century BCE and the Former and Latter Prophets were canonized by the second century BCE, the Ketuvim was not a fixed canon until the second century CE.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Evidence suggests, however, that the people of Israel were adding what would become the Ketuvim to their holy literature shortly after the canonization of the prophets.
[src:bible/bible-p02] As early as 132 BCE references suggest that the Ketuvim was starting to take shape, although it lacked a formal title.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Septuagint ("the Translation of the Seventy", also called "the LXX"), is a Koine Greek translation of the Hebrew Bible begun in the late third century BCE.
[src:bible/bible-p02] As the work of translation progressed, the Septuagint expanded: the collection of prophetic writings had various hagiographical works incorporated into it.
[src:bible/bible-p02] In addition, some newer books such as the Books of the Maccabees and the Wisdom of Sirach were added.
[src:bible/bible-p02] These are among the "apocryphal" books, (books whose authenticity is doubted).
[src:bible/bible-p02] The inclusion of these texts, and the claim of some mistranslations, contributed to the Septuagint being seen as a "careless" translation and its eventual rejection as a valid Jewish scriptural text.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The apocrypha are Jewish literature, mostly of the Second Temple period (c.
[src:bible/bible-p02] 550 BCE – 70 CE); they originated in Israel, Syria, Egypt or Persia; were originally written in Hebrew, Aramaic, or Greek, and attempt to tell of biblical characters and themes.
[src:bible/bible-p02] One older theory of where they came from asserted that an "Alexandrian" canon had been accepted among the Greek-speaking Jews living there, but that theory has since been abandoned.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Indications are that they were not accepted when the rest of the Hebrew canon was.
[src:bible/bible-p02] It is clear the Apocrypha were used in New Testament times, but "they are never quoted as Scripture." In modern Judaism, none of the apocryphal books are accepted as authentic and are therefore excluded from the canon.
[src:bible/bible-p02] However, "the Ethiopian Jews, who are sometimes called Falashas, have an expanded canon, which includes some Apocryphal books".
[src:bible/bible-p02] The rabbis also wanted to distinguish their tradition from the newly emerging tradition of Christianity.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Finally, the rabbis claimed a divine authority for the Hebrew language, in contrast to Aramaic or Greek – even though these languages were the *lingua franca* of Jews during this period (and Aramaic would eventually be given the status of a sacred language comparable to Hebrew).
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Book of Daniel is preserved in the 12-chapter Masoretic Text and in two longer Greek versions, the original Septuagint version, c.
[src:bible/bible-p02] 100 BCE, and the later Theodotion version from c. second century CE.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Both Greek texts contain three additions to Daniel: The Prayer of Azariah and Song of the Three Holy Children; the story of Susannah and the Elders; and the story of Bel and the Dragon.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Theodotion's translation was so widely copied in the Early Christian church that its version of the Book of Daniel virtually superseded the Septuagint's.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Theodotion's Daniel is closer to the surviving Hebrew Masoretic Text version, the text which is the basis for most modern translations.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Theodotion's Daniel is also the one embodied in the authorized edition of the Septuagint published by Sixtus V in 1587.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Textual critics are now debating how to reconcile the earlier view of the Septuagint as 'careless' with content from the Dead Sea Scrolls at Qumran, scrolls discovered at Wadi Murabba'at, Nahal Hever, and those discovered at Masada.
[src:bible/bible-p02] These scrolls are 1000–1300 years older than the Leningrad text, dated to 1008 CE, which forms the basis of the Masoretic text.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The scrolls have confirmed much of the Masoretic text, but they have also differed from it, and many of those differences agree with the Septuagint, the Samaritan Pentateuch or the Greek Old Testament instead.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Copies of some texts later declared apocryphal are also among the Qumran texts.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Ancient manuscripts of the book of Sirach, the "Psalms of Joshua", Tobit, and the Epistle of Jeremiah are now known to have existed in a Hebrew version.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Septuagint version of some biblical books, such as the Book of Daniel and Book of Esther, are longer than those in the Jewish canon.
[src:bible/bible-p02] In the Septuagint, Jeremiah is shorter than in the Masoretic text, but a shortened Hebrew Jeremiah has been found at Qumran in cave 4.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The scrolls of Isaiah, Exodus, Jeremiah, Daniel and Samuel exhibit striking and important textual variants from the Masoretic text.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Septuagint is now seen as a careful translation of a different Hebrew form or recension (revised addition of the text) of certain books, but debate on how best to characterize these varied texts is ongoing.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Pseudepigrapha are works whose authorship is wrongly attributed.
[src:bible/bible-p02] A written work can be pseudepigraphical and not be a forgery, as forgeries are intentionally deceptive.
[src:bible/bible-p02] With pseudepigrapha, authorship has been mistransmitted for any one of a number of reasons.
[src:bible/bible-p02] For example, the Gospel of Barnabas claims to be written by Barnabas the companion of the Apostle Paul, but both its manuscripts date from the Middle Ages.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Apocryphal and pseudepigraphic works are not the same.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Apocrypha includes all the writings claiming to be sacred that are outside the canon because they are not accepted as authentically being what they claim to be.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Pseudepigrapha is a literary category of all writings, whether they are canonical or apocryphal.
[src:bible/bible-p02] They may or may not be authentic in every sense except for a misunderstood authorship.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Notable pseudepigraphal works include the Books of Enoch such as 1 Enoch, 2 Enoch, which survives only in Old Slavonic, and 3 Enoch, surviving in Hebrew of the c. fifth century – c. sixth century CE.
[src:bible/bible-p02] These are ancient Jewish religious works, traditionally ascribed to the prophet Enoch, the great-grandfather of the patriarch Noah.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The fragment of Enoch found among the Qumran scrolls attests to it being an ancient work.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The older sections (mainly in the Book of the Watchers) are estimated to date from about 300 BCE, and the latest part (Book of Parables) was probably composed at the end of the first century BCE.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Enoch is not part of the biblical canon used by most Jews, apart from Beta Israel.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Most Christian denominations and traditions may accept the Books of Enoch as having some historical or theological interest or significance.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Part of the Book of Enoch is quoted in the Epistle of Jude and the Book of Hebrews (parts of the New Testament), but Christian denominations generally regard the Books of Enoch as non-canonical.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The exceptions to this view are the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church and Eritrean Orthodox Tewahedo Church.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Ethiopian Bible is not based on the Greek Bible, and the Ethiopian Church has a slightly different understanding of canon than other Christian traditions.
[src:bible/bible-p02] In Ethiopia, canon does not have the same degree of fixedness (yet neither is it completely open).
[src:bible/bible-p02] Enoch has long been seen there as inspired scripture, but being scriptural and being canon are not always seen the same.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The official Ethiopian canon has 81 books, but that number is reached in different ways with various lists of different books, and the book of Enoch is sometimes included and sometimes not.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Current evidence confirms Enoch as canonical in both Ethiopia and in Eritrea.
[src:bible/bible-p02] A Christian Bible is a set of books divided into the Old and New Testament that a Christian denomination has, at some point in their past or present, regarded as divinely inspired scripture by the Holy Spirit.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Early Church primarily used the Septuagint, as it was written in Greek, the common tongue of the day, or they used the Targums among Aramaic speakers.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Modern English translations of the Old Testament section of the Christian Bible are based on the Masoretic Text.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Pauline epistles and the gospels were soon added, along with other writings, as the New Testament.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Old Testament has been important to the life of the Christian church from its earliest days.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Wright says "Jesus himself was profoundly shaped by the scriptures." Wright adds that the earliest Christians searched those same Hebrew scriptures in their effort to understand the earthly life of Jesus.
[src:bible/bible-p02] They regarded the "holy writings" of the Israelites as necessary and instructive for the Christian, as seen from Paul's words to Timothy (2 Timothy 3:15), as pointing to the Messiah, and as having reached a climactic fulfilment in Jesus generating the "new covenant" prophesied by Jeremiah.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Protestant Old Testament of the 21st century has a 39-book canon.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The number of books (although not the content) varies from the Jewish Tanakh only because of a different method of division.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The term "Hebrew scriptures" is often used as being synonymous with the Protestant Old Testament, since the surviving scriptures in Hebrew include only those books.
[src:bible/bible-p02] However, the Roman Catholic Church recognizes 46 books as its Old Testament (45 if Jeremiah and Lamentations are counted as one), and the Eastern Orthodox Churches recognize six additional books.
[src:bible/bible-p02] These additions are also included in the Syriac versions of the Bible called the *Peshitta* and the Ethiopian Bible.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Because the canon of Scripture is distinct for Jews, Eastern Orthodox, Roman Catholics, and Western Protestants, the contents of each community's Apocrypha are unique, as is its usage of the term.
[src:bible/bible-p02] For Jews, none of the apocryphal books are considered canonical.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Catholics refer to this collection as "Deuterocanonical books" (second canon) and the Orthodox Church refers to them as "Anagignoskomena" (that which is read).
[src:bible/bible-p02] Books included in the Catholic, Orthodox, Greek, and Slavonic Bibles are: Tobit, Judith, the Wisdom of Solomon, Sirach (or Ecclesiasticus), Baruch, the Letter of Jeremiah (also called the Baruch Chapter 6), 1 Maccabees, 2 Maccabees, the Greek Additions to Esther and the Greek Additions to Daniel.
[src:bible/bible-p02] 2 Esdras (4 Esdras), which is not included in the Septuagint, does not exist in Greek, though it does exist in Latin.
[src:bible/bible-p02] There is also 4 Maccabees which is only accepted as canonical in the Georgian Church.
[src:bible/bible-p02] It is in an appendix to the Greek Orthodox Bible, and it is therefore sometimes included in collections of the Apocrypha.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Ethiopian Old Testament Canon uses Enoch and Jubilees (that only survived in Ge'ez), 1–3 Meqabyan, Greek Ezra, 2 Esdras, and Psalm 151.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Revised Common Lectionary of the Lutheran Church, Moravian Church, Reformed Churches, Anglican Church and Methodist Church uses the apocryphal books liturgically, with alternative Old Testament readings available.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Roman Catholic and Eastern Orthodox Churches use most of the books of the Septuagint, while Protestant churches usually do not.
[src:bible/bible-p02] After the Protestant Reformation, many Protestant Bibles began to follow the Jewish canon and exclude the additional texts, which came to be called *apocryphal*.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Apocrypha are included under a separate heading in the King James Version of the Bible, the basis for the Revised Standard Version.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The New Testament is the name given to the second portion of the Christian Bible.
[src:bible/bible-p02] While some scholars assert that Aramaic was the original language of the New Testament, the majority view says it was written in the vernacular form of Koine Greek.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Still, there is reason to assert that it is a heavily Semitized Greek: its syntax is like conversational Greek, but its style is largely Semitic.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Koine Greek was the common language of the western Roman Empire from the Conquests of Alexander the Great (335–323 BCE) until the evolution of Byzantine Greek (c.
[src:bible/bible-p02] 600) while Aramaic was the language of Jesus, the Apostles and the ancient Near East.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The term "New Testament" came into use in the second century during a controversy over whether the Hebrew Bible should be included with the Christian writings as sacred scripture.
[src:bible/bible-p02] It is generally accepted that the New Testament writers were Jews who took the inspiration of the Old Testament for granted.
[src:bible/bible-p02] This is probably stated earliest in 2 Timothy 3:16: "All scripture is given by inspiration of God".
[src:bible/bible-p02] Scholarship on how and why ancient Jewish–Christians came to create and accept new texts as equal to the established Hebrew texts has taken three forms.
[src:bible/bible-p02] First, priest and biblical scholar John Barton writes that ancient Christians probably just continued the Jewish tradition of writing and incorporating what they believed were inspired, authoritative religious books.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The second approach separates those various inspired writings based on a concept of "canon" which developed in the second century.
[src:bible/bible-p02] According to Barton, these differences are only differences in terminology; the ideas are reconciled if they are seen as three stages in the formation of the New Testament.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The first stage was completed remarkably early if one accepts Albert C.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Sundberg's view that "canon" and "scripture" are separate things, with "scripture" having been recognized by ancient Christians long before "canon" was.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Barton says Theodor Zahn concluded "there was already a Christian canon by the end of the first century", but this is not the canon of later centuries.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Accordingly, Sundberg asserts that in the first centuries, there was no criterion for inclusion in the "sacred writings" beyond inspiration, and that no one in the first century had the idea of a closed canon.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The gospels were accepted by early believers as handed down from those Apostles who had known Jesus and been taught by him.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Later biblical criticism has questioned the authorship and dating of the gospels.
[src:bible/bible-p02] At the end of the second century, it is widely recognized that a Christian canon similar to its modern version was asserted by the church fathers in response to the plethora of writings claiming inspiration that contradicted orthodoxy: (heresy).
[src:bible/bible-p02] The third stage of development as the final canon occurred in the fourth century with a series of synods that produced a list of texts of the canon of the Old Testament and the New Testament that are still used today.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Most notably the Synod of Hippo in 393 CE and that of *c*.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Jerome produced a definitive Latin edition of the Bible (the Vulgate), the canon of which, at the insistence of the Pope, was in accord with the earlier Synods.
[src:bible/bible-p02] This process effectively set the New Testament canon.
[src:bible/bible-p02] New Testament books already had considerable authority in the late first and early second centuries.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Even in its formative period, most of the books of the New Testament that were seen as scripture were already agreed upon.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Porter says "evidence from the apocryphal non-Gospel literature is the same as that for the apocryphal Gospels – in other words, that the text of the Greek New Testament was relatively well established and fixed by the time of the second and third centuries".
[src:bible/bible-p02] By the time the fourth century Fathers were approving the "canon", they were doing little more than codifying what was already universally accepted.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The New Testament is a collection of 27 books of 4 different genres of Christian literature (Gospels, one account of the Acts of the Apostles, Epistles and an Apocalypse).
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Gospels are narratives of Jesus's last three years of life, his death and resurrection.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The narrative literature provides an account and history of the very early Apostolic age.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Pauline epistles are written to individual church groups to address problems, provide encouragement and give instruction.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The pastoral epistles discuss the pastoral oversight of churches, Christian living, doctrine and leadership.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Catholic epistles, also called the general epistles or lesser epistles.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Catholicism, Protestantism, and Eastern Orthodox currently have the same 27-book New Testament Canon.
[src:bible/bible-p02] They are ordered differently in the Slavonic tradition, the Syriac tradition and the Ethiopian tradition.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Peshitta (Classical Syriac: ܦܫܺܝܛܬܳܐ *or* ܦܫܝܼܛܬܵܐ **pšīṭtā**) is the standard version of the Bible for churches in the Syriac tradition.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The consensus within biblical scholarship, although not universal, is that the Old Testament of the Peshitta was translated into Syriac from biblical Hebrew, probably in the 2nd century CE, and that the New Testament of the Peshitta was translated from the Greek.
[src:bible/bible-p02] This New Testament, originally excluding certain disputed books (2 Peter, 2 John, 3 John, Jude, Revelation), had become a standard by the early 5th century.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The five excluded books were added in the Harklean Version (616 CE) of Thomas of Harqel.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The canon of the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church is wider than the canons used by most other Christian churches.
[src:bible/bible-p02] There are 81 books in the Ethiopian Orthodox Bible.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The three books of Meqabyan are not to be confused with the books of Maccabees.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The order of the books is somewhat different in that the Ethiopian Old Testament follows the Septuagint order for the Minor Prophets rather than the Jewish order.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The New Testament apocrypha are a number of writings by early professed Christians that give accounts of Jesus and his teachings, the nature of God, or the teachings of his Apostles and of their activities.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Some of these writings were cited as Scripture by some early Christians, but since the fifth century a widespread consensus emerged limiting the New Testament to the 27 books of the modern canon.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Roman Catholic, Eastern Orthodox, and Western Protestant churches do not view the New Testament apocrypha as part of the inspired Bible.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Although some Oriental Orthodox canons to some extent have.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The Armenian Apostolic church at times has included the Third Epistle to the Corinthians, but does not always list it with the other 27 canonical New Testament books.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The New Testament of the Coptic Bible, adopted by the Egyptian Church, includes the two Epistles of Clement.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The original autographs, that is, the original Greek writings and manuscripts written by the original authors of the New Testament, have not survived.
[src:bible/bible-p02] But, historically, *copies* of those original autographs exist and were transmitted and preserved in a number of manuscript traditions.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The three main textual traditions of the Greek New Testament are sometimes called the Alexandrian text-type (generally minimalist), the Byzantine text-type (generally maximalist), and the Western text-type (occasionally wild).
[src:bible/bible-p02] Together they comprise most of the ancient manuscripts.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Very early on, Christianity replaced scrolls with codexes, the forerunner of bound books, and by the 3rd century, collections of biblical books began being copied as a set.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Since all ancient texts were written by hand, often by copying from another handwritten text, they are not exactly alike in the manner of printed works.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The differences between them are considered generally minor and are called textual variants.
[src:bible/bible-p02] A variant is simply any variation between two texts.
[src:bible/bible-p02] The majority of variants are accidental, but some are intentional.
[src:bible/bible-p02] Intentional changes were made to improve grammar, to eliminate discrepancies, to make Liturgical changes such as the doxology of the Lord's prayer, to harmonize parallel passages or to combine and simplify multiple variant readings into one.
[src:bible/bible-p03] With a literary tradition spanning two millennia, the Bible is one of the most influential works ever written.
[src:bible/bible-p03] From practices of personal hygiene to philosophy and ethics, the Bible has directly and indirectly influenced politics and law, war and peace, sexual morals, marriage and family life, letters and learning, the arts, economics, social justice, medical care and more.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Christian Bible is the world's most published book, with estimated total sales of over five billion copies.
[src:bible/bible-p03] As such, the Bible has had a profound influence, especially in the Western world, where the Gutenberg Bible was the first book printed in Europe using movable type.
[src:bible/bible-p03] It has contributed to the formation of Western law, art, literature, and education.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Bible has been used to support and oppose political power.
[src:bible/bible-p03] It has inspired revolution and "a reversal of power" because God is so often portrayed as choosing what is "weak and humble...(the stammering Moses, the infant Samuel, Saul from an insignificant family, David confronting Goliath, etc.)....to confound the mighty".
[src:bible/bible-p03] Biblical texts have been the catalyst for political concepts like democracy, religious toleration and religious freedom.
[src:bible/bible-p03] These have, in turn, inspired movements ranging from abolitionism in the 18th and 19th century, to the civil rights movement, the Anti-Apartheid Movement, and liberation theology in Latin America.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Bible has been the source of many peace movements and efforts at reconciliation around the world.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The roots of many modern laws can be found in the Bible's teachings on due process, fairness in criminal procedures, and equity in the application of the law.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Judges are told not to accept bribes (Deuteronomy 16:19), are required to be impartial to native and stranger alike (Leviticus 24:22; Deuteronomy 27:19), to the needy and the powerful alike (Leviticus 19:15), and to rich and poor alike (Deuteronomy 1:16, 17; Exodus 23:2–6).
[src:bible/bible-p03] The right to a fair trial, and fair punishment, is also found in the Bible (Deuteronomy 19:15; Exodus 21:23–25).
[src:bible/bible-p03] Those most vulnerable in a patriarchal society – children, women, and strangers – are singled out in the Bible for special protection (Psalm 72:2, 4).
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Bible has been noted by scholars as a significant influence on the development of nationhood and nationalism, first among ancient Jews and later in Christian societies.
[src:bible/bible-p03] For the ancient Jews, it served as "both a national history and a source of law", providing a framework that established shared ancestry, common history, legal codes, and cultural markers that defined Jewish collective identity.
[src:bible/bible-p03] It has been suggested that the practice of regular public readings of biblical texts during the Second Temple period facilitated the transmission of these identity-forming narratives across the wider Jewish public.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Several scholars argue that substantial portions of the Hebrew Bible—particularly the Deuteronomistic History and the Tetrateuch—were composed specifically to establish and reinforce a distinct Israelite ethnic and national identity.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Some scholars of nationalism, such as Adrian Hastings, contend that the model of ancient Israel presented in the Hebrew Bible provided the world with the original concept of nationhood, influencing the development of nationalism and European nation-states.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The prophets of the Hebrew Bible repeatedly admonish the people to practice justice, charity, and social responsibility.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Lockton writes that "The Poverty and Justice Bible (The Bible Society (UK), 2008) claims there are more than 2000 verses in the Bible dealing with the justice issues of rich-poor relations, exploitation and oppression".
[src:bible/bible-p03] Judaism practised charity and healing the sick but tended to limit these practices to their own people.
[src:bible/bible-p03] For Christians, the Old Testament statements are enhanced by multiple verses such as Matthew 10:8, Luke 10:9 and 9:2, and Acts 5:16 that say "heal the sick".
[src:bible/bible-p03] Authors Vern and Bonnie Bullough write in *The care of the sick: the emergence of modern nursing,* that this is seen as an aspect of following Jesus's example, since so much of his public ministry focused on healing.
[src:bible/bible-p03] In the process of following this command, monasticism in the third century transformed health care.
[src:bible/bible-p03] This produced the first hospital for the poor in Caesarea in the fourth century.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The biblical practices of feeding and clothing the poor, visiting prisoners, supporting widows and orphan children have had sweeping impact.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Bible's emphasis on learning has had formidable influence on believers and western society.
[src:bible/bible-p03] For centuries after the fall of the western Roman Empire, all schools in Europe were Bible-based church schools, and outside of monastic settlements, almost no one had the ability to read or write.
[src:bible/bible-p03] These schools eventually led to the West's first universities (created by the church) in the Middle Ages which have spread around the world in the modern day.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Protestant Reformers wanted all members of the church to be able to read the Bible, so compulsory education for both boys and girls was introduced.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Translations of the Bible into local vernacular languages have supported the development of national literatures and the invention of alphabets.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Biblical teachings on sexual morality changed the Roman empire, the millennium that followed, and have continued to influence society.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Rome's concept of sexual morality was centered on social and political status, power, and social reproduction (the transmission of social inequality to the next generation).
[src:bible/bible-p03] The biblical standard was a "radical notion of individual freedom centered around a libertarian paradigm of complete sexual agency".
[src:bible/bible-p03] Classicist Kyle Harper describes the change biblical teaching evoked as "a revolution in the rules of behavior, but also in the very image of the human being".
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Bible has directly and indirectly influenced literature: St Augustine's Confessions is widely considered the first autobiography in Western Literature.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Many masterpieces of Western art were inspired by biblical themes: from Michelangelo's *David* and *Pietà* sculptures, to Leonardo da Vinci's *Last Supper* and Raphael's various *Madonna* paintings.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Eve, the temptress who disobeys God's commandment, is probably the most widely portrayed figure in art.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Renaissance preferred the sensuous female nude, while the "femme fatale" Delilah from the nineteenth century onward demonstrates how the Bible and art both shape and reflect views of women.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Bible has many rituals of purification which speak of clean and unclean in both literal and metaphorical terms.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The biblical toilet etiquette encourages washing after all instances of defecation, hence the invention of the bidet.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Critics view certain biblical texts to be morally problematic.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Bible neither calls for nor condemns slavery outright, but there are verses that address dealing with it, and these verses have been used to support it, although the Bible has also been used to support abolitionism.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Some have written that supersessionism begins in the book of Hebrews where others locate its beginnings in the culture of the fourth century Roman empire.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Bible has been used to support the death penalty, patriarchy, sexual intolerance, the violence of total war, and colonialism.
[src:bible/bible-p03] In the Christian Bible, the violence of war is addressed four ways: pacifism, non-resistance; just war, and preventive war which is sometimes called crusade.
[src:bible/bible-p03] In the Hebrew Bible, there is *just war* and *preventive war* which includes the Amalekites, Canaanites, Moabites, and the record in Exodus, Deuteronomy, Joshua, and both books of Kings.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Collins, biblical scholar, writes that people throughout history have used these biblical texts to justify violence against their enemies.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Historian Nur Masalha argues that genocide is inherent in these commandments, and that they have served as inspirational examples of divine support for slaughtering national opponents.
[src:bible/bible-p03] However, the "applicability of the term [genocide] to earlier periods of history" is questioned by sociologists Frank Robert Chalk and Kurt Jonassohn.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Since most societies of the past endured and practised genocide, it was accepted at that time as "being in the nature of life" because of the "coarseness and brutality" of life; the moral condemnation associated with terms like genocide are products of modern morality.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The definition of what constitutes violence has broadened considerably over time.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Bible reflects how perceptions of violence changed for its authors.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Feminist biblical scholar Phyllis Trible, in her book *Texts of Terror*, tells four Bible stories of suffering in ancient Israel where women are the victims.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Tribble describes the Bible as "a mirror" that reflects humans, and human life, in all its "holiness and horror".
[src:bible/bible-p03] Biblical texts have always required interpretation, and this has given rise to multiple views and approaches according to the interplay between various religions and the book.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The primary source of Jewish commentary and interpretation of the Hebrew Bible is the Talmud.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Talmud, (which means study and learning), is a summary of ancient oral law and commentary on it.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Adin Steinsaltz writes that "if the Bible is the cornerstone of Judaism, then the Talmud is the central pillar".
[src:bible/bible-p03] Seen as the backbone of Jewish creativity, it is "a conglomerate of law, legend and philosophy, a blend of unique logic and shrewd pragmatism, of history and science, anecdotes and humor" all aimed toward the purpose of studying biblical Torah.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Christians often treat the Bible as a single book, and while Barton says they are "some of the most profound texts humanity has ever produced", liberals and moderates see it as a collection of books that are not perfect.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Conservative and fundamentalist Christians see the Bible differently and interpret it differently.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Christianity interprets the Bible differently than Judaism does with Islam providing yet another view.
[src:bible/bible-p03] How inspiration works and what kind of authority it means the Bible has are different for different traditions.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Second Epistle to Timothy claims, "All Scripture is breathed out by God and profitable for teaching, for reproof, for correction, and for training in righteousness" (2 Tim.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Within these broad beliefs many schools of hermeneutics operate.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Jewish antiquity attests to belief in sacred texts, and a similar belief emerges in the earliest of Christian writings.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Various texts of the Bible mention divine agency in relation to its writings.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Among adherents of biblical literalism, a minority, such as followers of the King-James-Only Movement, extend the claim of inerrancy only to a particular version.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Both Judaism and Christianity see the Bible as religiously and intellectually significant.
[src:bible/bible-p03] It provides insight into its time and into the composition of the texts, and it represents an important step in the development of thought.
[src:bible/bible-p03] It is used in communal worship, recited and memorized, provides personal guidance, a basis for counseling, church doctrine, religious culture (teaching, hymns and worship), and ethical standards.
[src:bible/bible-p03] As a result, there are teachings and creeds in Christianity and laws in Judaism that are seen by those religions as derived from the Bible which are not directly in the Bible.
[src:bible/bible-p03] For the Hebrew Bible, canonization is reserved for written texts, while sacralization reaches far back into oral tradition.
[src:bible/bible-p03] When sacred stories, such as those that form the narrative base of the first five books of the Bible, were performed, "not a syllable [could] be changed in order to ensure the magical power of the words to 'presentify' the divine".
[src:bible/bible-p03] Inflexibility protected the texts from a changing world.
[src:bible/bible-p03] When sacred oral texts began the move to written transmission, commentary began being worked in, but once the text was closed by canonization, commentary needed to remain outside.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Sacred written texts were thereafter accompanied by commentary, and such commentary was sometimes written and sometimes orally transmitted, as is the case in the Islamic Madrasa and the Jewish Yeshiva.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Arguing that Torah has had a definitive role in developing Jewish identity from its earliest days, John J.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Collins explains that regardless of genetics or land, it has long been true that one could become Jewish by observing the laws in the Torah, and that remains true in the modern day.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Christian religion and its sacred book are connected and influence one another, but the significance of the written text has varied throughout history.
[src:bible/bible-p03] For Christianity, holiness did not reside in the written text, or in any particular language, it resided in the Christ the text witnessed to.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Carr writes that this gave early Christianity a more 'flexible' view of the written texts.
[src:bible/bible-p03] One cause of the Reformation was the perceived need to reorient Christianity around its early text as authoritative.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Some Protestant churches still focus on the idea of *sola scriptura*, which sees scripture as the only legitimate religious authority.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Some denominations today support the use of the Bible as the only infallible source of Christian teaching.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Others, though, advance the concept of *prima scriptura* in contrast, meaning scripture primarily or scripture mainly.
[src:bible/bible-p03] In the 21st century, attitudes towards the significance of the Bible continue to differ.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Roman Catholics, High Church Anglicans, Methodists and Eastern Orthodox Christians stress the harmony and importance of both the Bible and sacred tradition in combination.
[src:bible/bible-p03] United Methodists see Scripture as the major factor in Christian doctrine, but they also emphasize the importance of tradition, experience, and reason.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Lutherans teach that the Bible is the sole source for Christian doctrine.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Muslims view the Bible as an original revelation from God; but the Jews and the Christians corrupted it through falsification and alteration (*Taḥrīf*), and therefore the Quran is revealed by God to the Islamic prophet Muhammad.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Rastafari view the Bible as essential to their religion, while the Unitarian Universalists view it as "one of many important religious texts".
[src:bible/bible-p03] The original texts of the Tanakh were almost entirely written in Hebrew with about one per cent in Aramaic.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The earliest translation of any Bible text is the Septuagint which translated the Hebrew into Greek.
[src:bible/bible-p03] As the first translation of any biblical literature, the translation that became the Septuagint was an unparalleled event in the ancient world.
[src:bible/bible-p03] This translation was made possible by a common Mediterranean culture where Semitism had been foundational to Greek culture.
[src:bible/bible-p03] In the Talmud, Greek is the only language officially allowed for translation.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Targum Onkelos is the Aramaic translation of the Hebrew Bible believed to have been written in the second century CE.
[src:bible/bible-p03] These texts attracted the work of various scholars, but a standardized text was not available before the 9th century.
[src:bible/bible-p03] There were different ancient versions of the Tanakh in Hebrew.
[src:bible/bible-p03] These were copied and edited in three different locations producing slightly varying results.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Masoretic scholars in Tiberias in ancient Palestine copied the ancient texts in Tiberian Hebrew.
[src:bible/bible-p03] A copy was recovered from the "Cave of Elijah" (the synagogue of Aleppo in the Judean desert) and is therefore referred to as the Aleppo Codex which dates to around 920.
[src:bible/bible-p03] This codex, which is over a thousand years old, was originally the oldest codex of the complete Tiberian Hebrew Bible.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Babylonian masoretes had also copied the early texts, and the Tiberian and Babylonian were later combined, using the Aleppo Codex and additional writings, to form the Ben-Asher masoretic tradition which is the standardized Hebrew Bible of today.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Aleppo Codex is no longer the oldest complete manuscript because, during riots in 1947, the Aleppo Codex was removed from its location, and about 40% of it was subsequently lost.
[src:bible/bible-p03] It must now rely on additional manuscripts, and as a result, the Aleppo Codex contains the most comprehensive collection of variant readings.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The oldest complete version of the Masoretic tradition is the Leningrad Codex from 1008.
[src:bible/bible-p03] It is the source for all modern Jewish and Christian translations.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Levidas writes that, "The Koine Greek New Testament is a non-translated work; most scholars agree on this – despite disagreement on the possibility that some passages may have appeared initially in Aramaic...
[src:bible/bible-p03] It is written in the Koine Greek of the first century [CE]".
[src:bible/bible-p03] Early Christians translated the New Testament into Old Syriac, Coptic, Ethiopic, and Latin, among other languages.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The earliest Latin translation was the Old Latin text, or *Vetus Latina*, which, from internal evidence, seems to have been made by several authors over a period of time.
[src:bible/bible-p03] Pope Damasus I (366–383) commissioned Jerome to produce a reliable and consistent text by translating the original Greek and Hebrew texts into Latin.
[src:bible/bible-p03] This translation became known as the Latin Vulgate Bible, in the 4th century CE (although Jerome expressed in his prologues to most deuterocanonical books that they were non-canonical).
[src:bible/bible-p03] In 1546, at the Council of Trent, Jerome's Vulgate translation was declared by the Roman Catholic Church to be the only authentic and official Bible in the Latin Church.
[src:bible/bible-p03] The Greek-speaking East continued to use the Septuagint translations of the Old Testament, and they had no need to translate the Greek New Testament.
[src:bible/bible-p03] This contributed to the East-West Schism.
